00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:45.360
[Amit Varma]: So Ajay, tell me a little bit about how your book has been doing in the last few weeks.

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:50.160
[Amit Varma]: Is it a load off your shoulders in the sense that now all of this knowledge, these ideas

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:55.280
[Amit Varma]: are actually out there in, you know, in a packaged form and is there a sense of relief?

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:58.480
[Guest 1]: Yeah, it felt great when the book was finished.

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:05.120
[Guest 1]: This is going to sound cliched, but the reception of the book has just been a surprise to me.

00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:11.920
[Guest 1]: I thought that this was going to be some obscure geeky book with people like Vivek and you

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:15.280
[Guest 1]: taking interest in it and just about nobody else.

00:04:15.280 --> 00:04:19.760
[Guest 1]: In fact, the book seems to have found a life of its own.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:27.480
[Guest 1]: In the first month after the release of the book, Kelkar and I got 60 speaking invitations

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:35.240
[Guest 1]: and I just seem to be going around the world doing conversations, doing podcast episodes

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:37.520
[Guest 1]: and so on about the book.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:41.520
[Guest 1]: And it's overwhelming how many people are finding the book to be exciting.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:48.000
[Guest 1]: I increasingly see bits of it creeping into the culture, which is the best thing imaginable.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:53.160
[Guest 1]: I was with Junaid Ahmed at a book conversation at the World Bank and he asked me, what's

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:55.680
[Guest 1]: your highest dream for this book in five years?

00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:59.880
[Guest 1]: And I said, the highest dream is that these ideas should become commonplace and nobody

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:02.440
[Guest 1]: should even remember they came from us.

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:04.680
[Guest 1]: And bits of that are already visible.

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And how have people actually in the business of policymaking responded to it?

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
[Guest 1]: I think it's too far from practice.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:11.960
[Guest 1]: I think this is still at the thinking levels.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:14.200
[Amit Varma]: Do they read?

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:15.200
[Amit Varma]: That's a very good question.

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:16.200
[Amit Varma]: Do they read?

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:20.160
[Amit Varma]: And one question no one can ask you Vivek is, do you write?

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:23.680
[Guest 2]: Because you have written some 24 pieces since the budget came out three days ago.

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:24.680
[Guest 2]: It feels like that.

00:05:24.680 --> 00:05:25.680
[Guest 2]: It's cliched.

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:31.640
[Guest 2]: I wrote just five this time and one was actually in Hindi, which was sort of a summary of the

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:32.640
[Amit Varma]: other four.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:37.640
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, one criticism I, not of you, but in general of commentators and pundits

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:43.240
[Amit Varma]: that I read on Twitter is that after people stop criticizing the government, you know,

00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:46.800
[Amit Varma]: they'll turn to the pundits because all the pundits will say the same old cliched things

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:51.720
[Amit Varma]: year after year that, oh, structural reforms are needed and no, these are just piecemeal

00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:53.800
[Amit Varma]: solutions and blah, blah, blah.

00:05:53.800 --> 00:05:56.480
[Amit Varma]: And after I read that tweet, I think Siddhanth made a tweet like that.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:00.080
[Amit Varma]: And then I came across one of your pieces which spoke of structural fixes.

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, I mean, these are cliches because they're true and it is true that structural fixes

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:05.280
[Amit Varma]: are needed.

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:09.920
[Amit Varma]: But just as a writer, how do you get past the not just the fact that you're writing

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:10.920
[Amit Varma]: five pieces?

00:06:10.920 --> 00:06:11.920
[Amit Varma]: How do you not repeat yourself?

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:15.040
[Amit Varma]: But how do you not stop repeating yourself year after year?

00:06:15.040 --> 00:06:17.520
[Guest 2]: Because you're basically the same thing, right?

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:20.880
[Guest 2]: I don't have a problem with repeating myself because a lot of people, you know, a lot of

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:25.120
[Guest 2]: writers have this that if you're repeating yourself, it's not the right thing.

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:29.200
[Guest 2]: But my point is, you know, if that's the right thing to say, then that's the right thing

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:30.200
[Guest 2]: to say.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:31.200
[Guest 2]: I mean, if it's a repeat, it's a repeat.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:32.200
[Guest 2]: I mean, how does it matter?

00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:38.400
[Guest 2]: I mean, see, I have grown up on, you know, masala Hindi movies, they're basically the

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:39.400
[Guest 2]: same, right?

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:44.680
[Guest 2]: Two boys, one girl, three songs, father doesn't like the boy, boy is poor.

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:48.080
[Guest 2]: But people used to enjoy, people watched it over and over again.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:52.600
[Guest 2]: What I'm trying to say is that when I do this, I'm not being mediocre.

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:54.320
[Guest 2]: But that's what it is.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:58.800
[Guest 2]: One is when you want to say the right things and two is that there is only so much that

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:02.760
[Amit Varma]: you can say against, you know, that is happening.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:07.520
[Amit Varma]: Don't shoot the messenger, that's what the truth is, blame the truth, not the truth teller,

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:08.520
[Amit Varma]: as it were.

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:13.200
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, before we kind of start talking about this specific budget, what it did, and

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:17.760
[Amit Varma]: frankly, a lot of it is already feels a bit meh and blah and all of that.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:22.340
[Amit Varma]: But before we kind of get down to the specifics, Ajay, I wanted to ask you, you've actually

00:07:22.340 --> 00:07:27.000
[Amit Varma]: been an insider in all of this, you've been part of the process, the process of kind of

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:31.480
[Amit Varma]: making a budget and, you know, getting things out there, give me a little bit of insight

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:37.080
[Amit Varma]: onto that, like how do bureaucrats and politicians think about economic policy per se?

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:41.480
[Guest 1]: My knowledge is old, I left the Ministry of Finance in 2005.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:45.480
[Guest 1]: I was reasonably aware of how things worked in the 90s as well.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:52.960
[Guest 1]: So let me describe that world and it may or may not tally up with what is done today.

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:57.720
[Guest 1]: So the way this used to work was like this, that there used to be something called a budget

00:07:57.720 --> 00:08:03.280
[Guest 1]: group in the Ministry of Finance, which consisted of the secretaries of the three departments,

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:08.360
[Guest 1]: the Department of Economic Affairs, which does economic policy, the Department of Revenue,

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:13.820
[Guest 1]: which used to do tax administration, and the Department of Expenditure, which is a bit

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:20.820
[Guest 1]: of an accounting operation, which has oversight over the money flows into the departments.

00:08:20.820 --> 00:08:26.440
[Guest 1]: These three secretaries, along with the chief economic advisor, would sit with the finance

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:28.380
[Guest 1]: minister every morning.

00:08:28.380 --> 00:08:35.000
[Guest 1]: So when I used to be in this, there used to be a budget group meeting every morning, and

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.520
[Guest 1]: these four civil servants would sit with the finance minister, and they would debate every

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:41.520
[Guest 1]: morning.

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:45.160
[Guest 1]: Partly, they would debate from scratch, what is it that we would like to do?

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:51.360
[Guest 1]: Partly, they would respond to the large number of notes and proposals and ideas and the impulses

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:53.280
[Guest 1]: that were coming from outside.

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:58.880
[Guest 1]: And day after day, over a two-month period, they would refine the concept of what we want

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:01.920
[Guest 1]: to do this year, where we want to go this year.

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:09.200
[Guest 1]: And that discussion led to these two critical documents that came out.

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:13.860
[Guest 1]: The first was the budget packet, and the other is the economic survey.

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:19.920
[Guest 1]: In the budget packet, it's partly a financial statement about how we propose to raise revenues

00:09:19.920 --> 00:09:23.280
[Guest 1]: and how we propose to spend that money.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:29.160
[Guest 1]: But alongside that is part A of the budget speech, which is a bit of a work plan statement.

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:35.420
[Guest 1]: So it's a promise that over the next one year, these are all the things that various departments

00:09:35.420 --> 00:09:39.880
[Guest 1]: of government, all over government, not just the Ministry of Finance, will do.

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:40.880
[Guest 1]: Why is this important?

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:43.520
[Guest 1]: This is important for three reasons.

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:49.160
[Guest 1]: The first is that the budget speech has a certain legal status as a cabinet resolution.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:54.400
[Guest 1]: So short of being a parliamentary law, it is a document to take seriously.

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:57.360
[Guest 1]: Every word matters in an almost legalistic way.

00:09:57.360 --> 00:10:01.840
[Guest 1]: So it's a commitment device where various departments of government commit themselves

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:03.720
[Guest 1]: that I'm going to do this.

00:10:03.720 --> 00:10:09.360
[Guest 1]: Second, in the same vein, because that budget speech is then backed up, was then backed

00:10:09.360 --> 00:10:17.160
[Guest 1]: up with a follow-up and a tracking mechanism through the year, that people all over government

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:21.240
[Guest 1]: would be held accountable for delivery on the sentences in that budget speech.

00:10:21.240 --> 00:10:25.000
[Guest 1]: So this tracking mechanism was introduced, I think, at the time when Yashwant Sinha was

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.280
[Guest 1]: minister, where every sentence in the budget speech is mapped to one responsible person

00:10:30.280 --> 00:10:32.240
[Guest 1]: somewhere in government.

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:36.880
[Guest 1]: And there would be a process of building a spreadsheet through the year that was an MIS

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:40.640
[Guest 1]: about the state of completion of what was done and what was not done.

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:44.480
[Guest 1]: So again, I think that's why the words in the budget speech matter.

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:45.680
[Guest 1]: It's not just a speech.

00:10:45.680 --> 00:10:51.320
[Guest 1]: It's a legalistic document where every word counts and the words are actions.

00:10:51.320 --> 00:10:53.280
[Guest 1]: They're not statements of aspiration.

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:56.160
[Guest 1]: They're not vacuous phrases.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:11:02.240
[Guest 1]: They're actually supposed to be almost legal sentences that are actionable and that can

00:11:02.240 --> 00:11:03.240
[Guest 1]: be evaluated.

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:04.240
[Guest 1]: Was it done?

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:05.240
[Guest 1]: Was it not done?

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:11.080
[Guest 1]: The third reason why part A of the budget speech matters, and it flows logically in

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:16.800
[Guest 1]: the budget process, is that in those years, in the 90s and in the 2000s, the Department

00:11:16.800 --> 00:11:22.360
[Guest 1]: of Economic Affairs was the engine of economic reform, not just of the Ministry of Finance.

00:11:22.360 --> 00:11:27.680
[Guest 1]: The Department of Economic Affairs was the engine of economic reform, and it used budget-making

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:31.920
[Guest 1]: power to negotiate reforms with other ministries.

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:39.960
[Guest 1]: So as an example, the Ministry of Civil Aviation would ask for money to do ABC, and the DEA

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:43.280
[Guest 1]: would say, yeah, we'll give you this money, but you've got to privatize the Bombay and

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.040
[Guest 1]: Delhi airports.

00:11:45.040 --> 00:11:50.480
[Guest 1]: So this is how deals were made, that surrounding every year's budget process, there would be

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:54.120
[Guest 1]: negotiations that are done for reforms in government more broadly.

00:11:54.120 --> 00:11:59.520
[Guest 1]: And that required that the DEA had to have an economics capability more broadly and be

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:04.840
[Guest 1]: able to negotiate meaningfully with every single secretary in government.

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:10.240
[Guest 1]: And then those promises would turn into sentences in the part A, where they become legalistic.

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:14.560
[Guest 1]: It's not just an informal promise that some department makes, which they can later on

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:15.560
[Guest 1]: renege on.

00:12:15.560 --> 00:12:21.320
[Guest 1]: Okay, so these are the three reasons why the budget is pretty important.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:26.680
[Guest 1]: It's a work plan for the year with some legal status behind it, with some negotiation that

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:28.540
[Guest 1]: has led up to it.

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:31.080
[Guest 1]: And it's the stuff that will get done at a high priority.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:33.480
[Guest 1]: Of course, other things can also be done.

00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:38.600
[Guest 1]: But this is like the minimum work plan of the year in terms of what government can do.

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:42.240
[Guest 1]: And now let me describe the role of the Economic Survey.

00:12:42.240 --> 00:12:48.800
[Guest 1]: The Economic Survey is a document that's built by the team of economists in the Department

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:51.420
[Guest 1]: of Economic Affairs led by the Chief Economic Advisor.

00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:54.660
[Guest 1]: It is not the policy statement of the government.

00:12:54.660 --> 00:13:00.280
[Guest 1]: It's a view of the world of the Chief Economic Advisor and the other economists in the Ministry

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:01.900
[Guest 1]: of Finance.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:06.800
[Guest 1]: It mattered because the Chief Economic Advisor was a member of that budget group.

00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:12.120
[Guest 1]: And the Chief Economic Advisor was the intellectual in that group, who was a part of every single

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:16.400
[Guest 1]: discussion that do you really think it's worth privatizing the Bombay and Delhi airport?

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:17.400
[Guest 1]: What's your intellectual construct?

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.400
[Guest 1]: What's your intellectual framework?

00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:20.160
[Guest 1]: How are we going to think about it?

00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:23.720
[Guest 1]: The CEA was present in every budget discussion.

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:26.920
[Guest 1]: And by the way, in those years, the CEA would draft the budget speech.

00:13:26.920 --> 00:13:30.520
[Guest 1]: Because the CEA generally had the best writing capabilities compared to many of the career

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:33.900
[Guest 1]: civil servants whose written English is often quite poor.

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:42.340
[Guest 1]: So the CEA was the intellectual who cast a light of economics into every budget discussion.

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:48.040
[Guest 1]: And also personally was the author of the budget speech, the quality of language, the

00:13:48.040 --> 00:13:50.020
[Guest 1]: coherence of the budget speech.

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:55.460
[Guest 1]: You can see that richly say in the July 1991 budget speech, or what I experienced some

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:58.920
[Guest 1]: of the budget speeches written by Rakesh Mohan, and so on.

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:00.680
[Guest 1]: So that was the unique role of the CEA.

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:03.560
[Guest 1]: Now, that's all the policy work of the CEA.

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:09.180
[Guest 1]: But you and I as private citizens would find it interesting to read the Economic Survey

00:14:09.180 --> 00:14:14.440
[Guest 1]: because it gave a window into the intellectual framework of the CEA and of the economics

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:16.840
[Guest 1]: team inside the Ministry of Finance.

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:21.120
[Guest 1]: Not that they control economic policy, not that they make economic policy.

00:14:21.120 --> 00:14:27.480
[Guest 1]: But that they had a seat on the table in all the discussions and influenced the worldview

00:14:27.480 --> 00:14:30.040
[Guest 1]: and the philosophy of the Ministry of Finance.

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:34.480
[Guest 1]: Because otherwise, the career civil servants tend to not have much of a worldview.

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:36.500
[Guest 1]: They tend to do more expediency.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:37.720
[Guest 1]: This was the old arrangement.

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:43.520
[Guest 1]: And so that was the significance of the part A of the budget speech and the Economic Survey

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:44.520
[Guest 1]: and the budget process.

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Now, a couple of thoughts kind of strike me here.

00:14:48.600 --> 00:14:50.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, a couple of questions.

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:54.040
[Amit Varma]: One is that, which you can answer in a yes or no right away, which is that structurally

00:14:54.040 --> 00:14:55.800
[Guest 1]: are things more or less the same?

00:14:55.800 --> 00:14:57.160
[Guest 1]: I think they've changed quite a bit.

00:14:57.160 --> 00:14:59.760
[Guest 1]: I'm not competent on how things work today.

00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And the other question is even assuming that there is a structure which is similar to this

00:15:02.840 --> 00:15:06.240
[Amit Varma]: with little bits of change here and there.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:13.280
[Amit Varma]: What strikes me is that the smooth functioning of this seems to depend on having, say, the

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:17.000
[Amit Varma]: right individual with the right impulses in the right places.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.440
[Amit Varma]: For example, you talk about, you know, the third aspect of the budget that you pointed

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:25.600
[Amit Varma]: out that it became a tool for the Department of Economic Affairs to negotiate reforms with

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:26.600
[Amit Varma]: other departments.

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:30.280
[Amit Varma]: For example, civil aviation will give this budget if you privatize these airports.

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:32.040
[Amit Varma]: Now, that works both ways.

00:15:32.040 --> 00:15:36.480
[Amit Varma]: For example, if you assume as in public choice, you'd assume that there's certainly a direction

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:39.400
[Amit Varma]: towards all ministries being captured by special interests.

00:15:39.400 --> 00:15:44.720
[Amit Varma]: Now, if that is to be the case, and if that holds true of economic affairs as well, and

00:15:44.720 --> 00:15:49.680
[Amit Varma]: you don't have a utopian situation of actually having someone there who is reform minded

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:54.080
[Amit Varma]: and thinks about policy the right way, then what you have is really a negotiation between

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:55.680
[Amit Varma]: special interests.

00:15:55.680 --> 00:15:59.200
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, none of the reforms that we kind of speak out which are for the larger

00:15:59.200 --> 00:16:05.580
[Amit Varma]: good ever really happen, because then you're just negotiating transactional stuff.

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:08.680
[Guest 1]: So I want to take you back into history.

00:16:08.680 --> 00:16:14.280
[Guest 1]: We had a terrible time in the 70s and the 80s, in terms of the working of institutions

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:15.340
[Guest 1]: in India.

00:16:15.340 --> 00:16:21.160
[Guest 1]: And that gave us a balance of payments crisis, and an IMF program in 81 and 91.

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:31.080
[Guest 1]: And after that, a larger consciousness developed in the Indian government process, that there

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:35.300
[Guest 1]: is something special and important about the Ministry of Finance, about the Department

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:36.960
[Guest 1]: of Economic Affairs.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:41.440
[Guest 1]: And there was a very self conscious attempt at building a certain kind of capability in

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:43.280
[Guest 1]: the Department of Economic Affairs.

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:47.920
[Guest 1]: I remember, there was a time when I was in the Department of Economic Affairs, where

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:54.120
[Guest 1]: we were just playing games, sitting over chai and arguing about things.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:17:00.480
[Guest 1]: And we had the rough calculation with paper and pen, that if the economists in the Department

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest 1]: of Economic Affairs stepped out and became a new academic economics department in the

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.200
[Guest 1]: country, we would be the number one economics department in the country.

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:16.240
[Guest 1]: That was the kind of firepower that had accumulated in the DEA in those years.

00:17:16.240 --> 00:17:22.300
[Guest 1]: So in similar fashion, I just want to talk about tax policy, where your question shines

00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:24.760
[Guest 1]: through very nicely.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:31.000
[Guest 1]: When you have tax policy that is being controlled by the Department of Revenue, then you have

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:37.060
[Guest 1]: a real problem because the tax administrators will choose tax policy that is convenient

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:38.520
[Guest 1]: for themselves.

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:44.600
[Guest 1]: And one of the historic achievements of the 91 onwards period is that the primacy in tax

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:49.320
[Guest 1]: policy shifted from the Department of Revenue to the Department of Economic Affairs.

00:17:49.320 --> 00:17:56.200
[Guest 1]: Elsewhere in the world, this is done explicitly, that in places like the UK and the US, there

00:17:56.200 --> 00:18:00.880
[Guest 1]: is no role for tax administrators in determining tax policy.

00:18:00.880 --> 00:18:05.840
[Guest 1]: We didn't do that institutionally in India, but de facto, that's what happened in India

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:11.760
[Guest 1]: also starting from the 91 reforms, that we got great progress in tax policy.

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:16.400
[Guest 1]: You may recall, we started out with a big marginal income tax rate, like 98%.

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:17.400
[Guest 1]: We had a wealth tax.

00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:21.960
[Guest 1]: We had all sorts of craziness going on in tax policy, when tax policy was dominated

00:18:21.960 --> 00:18:25.220
[Guest 1]: by the tax administrators.

00:18:25.220 --> 00:18:30.960
[Guest 1]: And from 91 onwards, the primacy of tax policy moved out to DEA.

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:36.740
[Guest 1]: And somewhere in the last 15 years, tax policy went back to the Department of Revenue.

00:18:36.740 --> 00:18:41.800
[Guest 1]: And that's part of a lot of the troubles that we've been having in terms of the conduct

00:18:41.800 --> 00:18:43.760
[Guest 1]: of how India thinks about taxes.

00:18:43.760 --> 00:18:50.360
[Guest 1]: So this is an example of the role of an economics team in DEA to think about taxes as opposed

00:18:50.360 --> 00:18:54.720
[Guest 1]: to letting it be controlled by the tax administrators.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:58.400
[Amit Varma]: And would it be correct to say, like, I tend to be skeptical about the drift of government

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:00.240
[Amit Varma]: towards being captured.

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:04.840
[Amit Varma]: And would it be correct to say that, okay, 91, we were lucky that we had that crisis.

00:19:04.840 --> 00:19:08.420
[Amit Varma]: And all the reforms that happened, happened not just in terms of policy, but in terms

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:12.880
[Amit Varma]: of actually getting people in department who had a strategic vision, who looked at the

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:15.060
[Amit Varma]: bigger picture and got this stuff through.

00:19:15.060 --> 00:19:19.400
[Amit Varma]: But what appears to have happened since then, and even though you haven't been in the ministry,

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:21.120
[Amit Varma]: you've been close enough to comment on it.

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And what appears to have happened is a drift back to the old kind of system where your

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:31.280
[Amit Varma]: chief economic advisor is not necessarily any more an academic who is, you know, the

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:34.840
[Amit Varma]: big alpha in the room respected by everyone, a person with a vision.

00:19:34.840 --> 00:19:39.240
[Amit Varma]: But perhaps like in this case, frankly, I must say to political crony who is there because

00:19:39.240 --> 00:19:44.200
[Amit Varma]: he wrote columns in support of demonetization, which not many respectable economists would

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:45.200
[Amit Varma]: do.

00:19:45.200 --> 00:19:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And I won't ask you to comment on that.

00:19:46.200 --> 00:19:51.760
[Amit Varma]: And again, like you pointed out, tax policy going back into the hands of tax administration.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:56.240
[Amit Varma]: So two questions, is this sort of some kind of cyclical thing which can be reversed or

00:19:56.240 --> 00:20:01.400
[Amit Varma]: is it necessarily as I would skeptically say, that the tendency of government to be captured

00:20:01.400 --> 00:20:03.120
[Guest 1]: power and money, the interplay.

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:08.840
[Guest 1]: So I want to again, locate this in our historical experience, as Kelkar emphasizes, at the time

00:20:08.840 --> 00:20:15.000
[Guest 1]: of the 1991 reforms, there was actually remarkable capabilities in the community.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.960
[Guest 1]: There were people in many parts of government.

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:22.720
[Guest 1]: There was a very strong academic community, which had understood that the old Indian socialism

00:20:22.720 --> 00:20:28.040
[Guest 1]: was broken, which had thought hard about the kinds of changes that we might like to see.

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:33.560
[Guest 1]: And then in that context, when the crisis came, there was a capability in doing something

00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:34.560
[Guest 1]: differently.

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:40.400
[Guest 1]: And as you know, in the book, we actually belabor this point that don't overstate the

00:20:40.400 --> 00:20:45.160
[Guest 1]: extent to which a crisis will give us the requisite changes.

00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:51.240
[Guest 1]: Pakistan has had 14 IMF programs and never bootstrapped itself out of a low level equilibrium.

00:20:51.240 --> 00:20:59.720
[Guest 1]: So I would emphasize some very high minded people who took away the lessons of the 81

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:05.840
[Guest 1]: and the 91 IMF programs and the balance of payments crisis, who thought about how to

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:07.960
[Guest 1]: do things differently.

00:21:07.960 --> 00:21:14.120
[Guest 1]: And who took one key lesson away that you need to build intellectual and professional

00:21:14.120 --> 00:21:18.360
[Guest 1]: capability in the Ministry of Finance in the Department of Economic Affairs.

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:24.600
[Guest 1]: For example, there was a break in convention when Monte Carlo Alia became the finance secretary,

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:28.760
[Guest 1]: who was the first amongst equals, even though he was not the most senior of the secretaries,

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:30.400
[Guest 1]: but that's the right way to do it.

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:35.560
[Guest 1]: It is only the secretary, Department of Economic Affairs, who has the full picture, who should

00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:37.680
[Guest 1]: be the finance secretary.

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:44.480
[Guest 1]: And these are not things that can be easily messed with and you are able to then maintain

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:45.480
[Guest 1]: performance.

00:21:45.480 --> 00:21:50.280
[Guest 1]: So I think that we need to introspect a lot more about these institutional foundations

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:52.480
[Guest 1]: of good economic policy.

00:21:52.480 --> 00:21:57.600
[Guest 2]: What I wanted to ask you, Ajay, is that, you know, we have this funny thing, you have one

00:21:57.600 --> 00:22:03.160
[Guest 2]: guy who's finance secretary one day, and then becomes tourism secretary the next day.

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:07.840
[Guest 2]: So how do you get, you know, we live in the era of specialization.

00:22:07.840 --> 00:22:10.960
[Guest 2]: So how is this some sort of a joke or?

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:19.780
[Guest 1]: Well, the best civil servants are good managers, they will reply that is Steve Jobs an engineer?

00:22:19.780 --> 00:22:22.080
[Guest 1]: Is Tim Cook an engineer?

00:22:22.080 --> 00:22:28.880
[Guest 1]: So I think that the truth is halfway, that you do need leadership skills.

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:30.720
[Guest 1]: Leadership is a very human capability.

00:22:30.720 --> 00:22:34.120
[Guest 1]: It's about a certain kind of charisma, it's about handling people, it's about pulling

00:22:34.120 --> 00:22:39.200
[Guest 1]: technical teams together of geeks, and being able to get work out of many, many geeks.

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:43.840
[Guest 1]: It's about communications capabilities, it's about good human capabilities of being well

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:47.280
[Guest 1]: liked by people below and above you.

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:50.080
[Guest 1]: So I will give that to the leader.

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:51.760
[Guest 1]: But it's also about understanding, right?

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:56.080
[Guest 1]: So you do need a body of knowledge, and it does need a certain kind of capability.

00:22:56.080 --> 00:23:01.640
[Guest 1]: So I'm not one of those who will argue that you always need to be a professional economist

00:23:01.640 --> 00:23:03.320
[Guest 1]: to be a good secretary DEA.

00:23:03.320 --> 00:23:10.440
[Guest 1]: But I will also say that you do what in government is called 10-20 years in finance.

00:23:10.440 --> 00:23:15.080
[Guest 1]: So you know, look, an ideal person will have spent 5-10 years in a finance department in

00:23:15.080 --> 00:23:23.800
[Guest 1]: Tamil Nadu, will have spent some time at the IMF, will have grown up the hierarchy inside

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:27.680
[Guest 1]: the Ministry of Finance, will have gone a little bit distance away, Economic Advisory

00:23:27.680 --> 00:23:32.320
[Guest 1]: Council to the Prime Minister, you know, and then developed 10-20-30 years of job relevant

00:23:32.320 --> 00:23:36.960
[Guest 1]: experience, which is the ideal preparation to do DEA.

00:23:36.960 --> 00:23:41.240
[Guest 1]: And that used to be the way things were done in the past, and it's less so today.

00:23:41.240 --> 00:23:45.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, to add a little bit to the point that Vivek was making, the fundamental difference

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:50.680
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me between, say, Steve Jobs and a bureaucrat is the incentives at play, that,

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:55.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, you only rise in the private sector if you perform, you know, we think of Steve

00:23:55.040 --> 00:23:58.960
[Amit Varma]: Jobs because of the survivorship bias, he's a guy who happened to perform at that insane

00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:00.600
[Amit Varma]: level and got up there.

00:24:00.600 --> 00:24:03.800
[Amit Varma]: And it is relevant what he was trained in, he was very good at what he did.

00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:06.920
[Amit Varma]: And there was a way of measuring that, which is something that the market did.

00:24:06.920 --> 00:24:11.680
[Guest 1]: To be fair, Steve Jobs had the genius for asking a question, let's build something like

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:13.880
[Guest 1]: an iPod, or an iPad.

00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:16.160
[Guest 1]: But he didn't really know anything about how to do it.

00:24:16.160 --> 00:24:17.160
[Guest 1]: That's a distinction I want to make.

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:18.160
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:22.240
[Amit Varma]: But I'm saying that genius gets rewarded in the free market, in government, basically

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:27.240
[Amit Varma]: where you rank in the IAS exam, which you, the civil, the UPSC exam, which you give when

00:24:27.240 --> 00:24:31.400
[Amit Varma]: you're 20-21 will determine promotions for the rest of your career.

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:36.600
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, if you were going to judge, say, Steve Jobs on what he was doing at 21,

00:24:36.600 --> 00:24:37.600
[Guest 2]: you know, he probably...

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:39.040
[Guest 2]: But I think Ajay answered my question.

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:43.200
[Guest 2]: I mean, what I was basically trying to say is that, I mean, I was also not even for a

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:47.880
[Guest 2]: moment suggesting that the head of DEA should be an economist, but there has to be some

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:49.680
[Guest 2]: experience along the way.

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:54.200
[Guest 2]: But you know, so I find it very funny that, so Arvind Mayaram, excellent example, was

00:24:54.200 --> 00:24:57.080
[Guest 2]: the finance secretary, and then they made him the tourism secretary.

00:24:57.080 --> 00:25:01.320
[Guest 2]: Now tourism in itself is a very, very specialized area.

00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:02.320
[Guest 2]: So is finance.

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:05.760
[Guest 2]: So, I find that a little, you know, difficult to handle.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:09.120
[Guest 2]: Because I mean, the same thing happened with Subhash Chandragaru, you know, he was finance

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:13.640
[Guest 2]: secretary, and then he was made power secretary, the power in, you know, the kind of regulations

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:16.000
[Guest 2]: and everything that are there in India.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.880
[Guest 2]: It is a, it's a minefield in itself.

00:25:18.880 --> 00:25:19.880
[Guest 1]: Exactly.

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:25.680
[Guest 1]: So Vivek, on the way in, on the people who rise into the DEA, some of the most important

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:30.080
[Guest 1]: stints that they do are at a much younger level, when they are a director level officer,

00:25:30.080 --> 00:25:34.680
[Guest 1]: when they're a joint secretary, if they've done time inside the DEA, that really helps.

00:25:34.680 --> 00:25:40.480
[Guest 1]: So DEA is actually the ground in which we grow the future leadership cadre for economic

00:25:40.480 --> 00:25:41.480
[Guest 1]: policy.

00:25:41.480 --> 00:25:44.400
[Guest 1]: Or again, that is the way things were done many, many years ago.

00:25:44.400 --> 00:25:47.800
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, what role do political incentives play, for example, in the last episode, you

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:53.000
[Amit Varma]: did point out that it is in one sense, to the interest of a party to actually, you know,

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:56.360
[Amit Varma]: have a shadow cabinet and have competent people running their economic policy.

00:25:56.360 --> 00:25:59.680
[Amit Varma]: And when they come to government, you know, start implementing that while you have your

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:03.280
[Amit Varma]: five year term ahead of you, which seems to make sense.

00:26:03.280 --> 00:26:07.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, if all that was there in politics was you come to power, you govern well, and

00:26:07.200 --> 00:26:09.720
[Amit Varma]: on the basis of the governance, you get elected again.

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:11.400
[Amit Varma]: But that's not exactly how the chain is.

00:26:11.400 --> 00:26:15.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, if you look at the current party in power, you don't have that situation where

00:26:15.560 --> 00:26:20.120
[Amit Varma]: they seem to value that kind of governance and building that kind of competence.

00:26:20.120 --> 00:26:26.680
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if you, you know, they started with a bunch of pretty remarkable economists in

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:31.040
[Amit Varma]: their team, so to say with Raghuram Rajan and Subramanian and all of that, and they

00:26:31.040 --> 00:26:36.960
[Amit Varma]: all kind of left and, you know, even those who have remained, I think, have, to some

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:42.520
[Amit Varma]: extent, debased themselves by supporting things like demonetization and defending the monstrosity

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:45.280
[Amit Varma]: that the GST has become.

00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:50.360
[Amit Varma]: Is the politics in part responsible for the degradation of the process like you've kind

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:51.360
[Amit Varma]: of described?

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:54.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the process has degraded, you would accept.

00:26:54.320 --> 00:27:02.920
[Guest 1]: Vivek, if I may, again, I think I'm halfway to, again, make an analogy with corporations.

00:27:02.920 --> 00:27:08.920
[Guest 1]: In Hindustan Lever, you will want a phenomenal capability in branding and in marketing and

00:27:08.920 --> 00:27:09.920
[Guest 1]: in distribution.

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:14.400
[Guest 1]: Okay, but all the branding and the marketing and the distribution is not a substitute for

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:19.320
[Guest 1]: actually the R&D that develops good products, and the manufacturing and the supply chain

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:22.400
[Guest 1]: management that delivers the products all over the country.

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:24.880
[Guest 1]: So I think it's not either or, it's both.

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:32.840
[Guest 1]: Now, my opinion is that the politicians of that period took away a lesson from the balance

00:27:32.840 --> 00:27:37.880
[Guest 1]: of payments crisis of 81 and of 91, saying that this is too costly for us.

00:27:37.880 --> 00:27:43.880
[Guest 1]: So let's build an intellectual capability in economic policy, and then we'll, of course,

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:45.160
[Guest 1]: go on and do our politics.

00:27:45.160 --> 00:27:47.800
[Guest 1]: So all of us know the history of that period.

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:54.320
[Guest 1]: It's not as if post-91 politics was characterized by consistent greatness, they were not paragons

00:27:54.320 --> 00:27:55.320
[Guest 1]: of excellence.

00:27:55.320 --> 00:27:57.480
[Guest 1]: It was a practical and logical thing to do.

00:27:57.480 --> 00:28:02.520
[Guest 1]: So I think that the Indian political system has to ask itself, what are the costs and

00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:07.800
[Guest 1]: benefits of greater intellectual capacity in the economic policy process?

00:28:07.800 --> 00:28:12.840
[Guest 1]: We've seen various kinds of experiments of doing it more and doing it less, and let history

00:28:12.840 --> 00:28:19.840
[Guest 1]: judge what is the most useful thing to do, and whether there is a causal connection between

00:28:19.840 --> 00:28:25.320
[Guest 1]: the kind of Department of Economic Affairs that you build and the kind of long-term growth

00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:26.520
[Guest 1]: outcomes that you get.

00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:28.900
[Guest 1]: The links are not there in the short term.

00:28:28.900 --> 00:28:35.440
[Guest 1]: In the short term, it will always appear that there are no consequences to diminishing the

00:28:35.440 --> 00:28:42.520
[Guest 1]: institutional capacity of the DEA and of the other economic policy institutional apparatus.

00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:44.440
[Guest 1]: But is there a link in the medium term?

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:46.520
[Guest 1]: Is there a link in the long term?

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:48.920
[Guest 1]: I believe the answer is yes.

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:55.520
[Guest 1]: And it is for the people in politics to debate whether those kinds of time horizons and those

00:28:55.520 --> 00:29:01.160
[Guest 1]: considerations of performance are salient when thinking about their own optimization.

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:02.720
[Amit Varma]: No, that's fair enough.

00:29:02.720 --> 00:29:06.200
[Amit Varma]: And that's again a problem we again, I won't go over at ground again, we discussed it in

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:10.960
[Amit Varma]: the episode we did where the issue is that a politician always has a very short time

00:29:10.960 --> 00:29:12.200
[Amit Varma]: horizon in front of him.

00:29:12.200 --> 00:29:15.880
[Amit Varma]: The next election is not even five years away, it's all the time because state elections

00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:17.760
[Amit Varma]: keep happening all the time.

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:21.960
[Amit Varma]: And if you are asked to build capacity or do things that will pay off in the extreme

00:29:21.960 --> 00:29:26.440
[Amit Varma]: long term, what are the sort of incentives there?

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:32.320
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, Vivek, if I may turn to you, one of Ajay's colleagues at NIPFP,

00:29:32.320 --> 00:29:37.000
[Amit Varma]: a former colleague, Suyash Rai, who is now at Carnegie India, wrote this piece where

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:41.600
[Amit Varma]: he said that this budget is more tactics and strategy.

00:29:41.600 --> 00:29:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And do you think that that is a case that there is the absence of somebody sitting in

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:49.400
[Amit Varma]: making an overall plan?

00:29:49.400 --> 00:29:53.200
[Amit Varma]: Because at one level, you could say that a lot of it is piecemeal announcements, yeh

00:29:53.200 --> 00:29:58.600
[Amit Varma]: karenge, woh karenge, and possibly the result of sort of different silos within the government

00:29:58.600 --> 00:30:00.720
[Amit Varma]: demanding this or demanding that.

00:30:00.720 --> 00:30:02.400
[Amit Varma]: And there's no overall broader vision.

00:30:02.400 --> 00:30:03.400
[Guest 2]: Is that a sense you're getting?

00:30:03.400 --> 00:30:06.720
[Guest 2]: I haven't read Suyash's piece, so I don't know.

00:30:06.720 --> 00:30:09.240
[Guest 2]: But what I can, I mean, I can, I'll give you an example here.

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:16.840
[Guest 2]: So, in this year's economic survey, and also in the speech, in Finance Minister's speech,

00:30:16.840 --> 00:30:23.040
[Guest 2]: was a mention of the fact that we need to become a part of global supply chains, okay.

00:30:23.040 --> 00:30:30.200
[Guest 2]: So, exports over the last, let's say, 20 years have happened if you are a part of global

00:30:30.200 --> 00:30:31.200
[Guest 2]: supply chain.

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:33.480
[Guest 2]: I mean, like, take the example of China, right.

00:30:33.480 --> 00:30:36.080
[Guest 2]: In fact, the best example is that of the iPhone.

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:40.840
[Guest 2]: So, everything that goes into the iPhone is made in different parts of the world, and

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:43.600
[Guest 2]: then it gets assembled in China, right.

00:30:43.600 --> 00:30:48.920
[Guest 2]: So, in that sense, China is a part of a global value chain.

00:30:48.920 --> 00:30:52.920
[Guest 2]: Now, it may obviously be that assembling is the probably the lowest part of the value

00:30:52.920 --> 00:30:57.520
[Guest 2]: chain, but it helps because it is a labor intensive industry, right.

00:30:57.520 --> 00:31:00.560
[Guest 2]: Years later, we have started to talk about it.

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:05.400
[Guest 2]: Now, at the same time, there has been a rise in protectionism.

00:31:05.400 --> 00:31:09.720
[Guest 2]: In fact, Arun Jaitley, in the last budget speech that he made, said very, very clearly

00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:15.080
[Guest 2]: that, you know, we are going against what has been policy for the last 20-25 years.

00:31:15.080 --> 00:31:22.000
[Guest 2]: So, now, the moment you start, you know, going towards protectionism, you're obviously, you

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.960
[Guest 2]: know, allowing the local guy not to compete.

00:31:25.960 --> 00:31:30.880
[Guest 2]: And if you can't compete, you know, how do you become a part of the global supply chain?

00:31:30.880 --> 00:31:32.920
[Guest 2]: So, there is an inherent contradiction.

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:37.000
[Guest 2]: At one part, you're talking about the fact that we need to export more, become a, you

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.240
[Guest 2]: know, part of a global supply chain, and so on and so forth.

00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:43.760
[Guest 2]: And on the other part, you're increasing custom duties on products.

00:31:43.760 --> 00:31:48.160
[Guest 2]: So, something as simple as I was talking to, you know, some random guy, and he was telling

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:51.520
[Guest 2]: me about something as simple as porcelain plates, right.

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:58.040
[Guest 2]: Now, a lot of hotels, you know, they imported from China simply because we don't make those

00:31:58.040 --> 00:31:59.040
[Guest 2]: plates in India.

00:31:59.040 --> 00:32:00.960
[Guest 2]: We don't make plates which are good enough in India.

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:05.960
[Guest 2]: So, like, something like, you know, a big hotel would require a plate which can be loaded

00:32:05.960 --> 00:32:07.280
[Guest 2]: onto a dishwasher.

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:11.360
[Guest 2]: So, that kind of product is not available in India.

00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:16.800
[Guest 2]: Now, the moment you increase the customs duty on that, you're essentially making his life

00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:17.800
[Guest 2]: difficult.

00:32:17.800 --> 00:32:24.440
[Guest 2]: So, it's not, so, see, I find it very difficult when, you know, when people say, Chinese product.

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:28.640
[Guest 2]: But the point is, at the end of the day, no one is forcing an average Indian to buy a

00:32:28.640 --> 00:32:29.920
[Guest 2]: Chinese product, right.

00:32:29.920 --> 00:32:35.400
[Guest 2]: We buy Chinese products, knowingly, if, I mean, a lot of people buy unknowingly as well.

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:39.720
[Guest 2]: But if you're buying a Chinese product knowingly, you're doing it because you feel that the

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:42.520
[Guest 2]: product has more value for money.

00:32:42.520 --> 00:32:47.680
[Guest 2]: So, the moment, you know, you start talking about protectionism, you're essentially going

00:32:47.680 --> 00:32:50.160
[Guest 2]: against the average consumer.

00:32:50.160 --> 00:32:53.320
[Guest 2]: And you know, I mean, this is something you and I have discussed over and over again,

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:58.160
[Guest 2]: that when you sort of increase protectionism, the scene effect is that someone benefits.

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:01.200
[Guest 2]: But there are a whole lot of unseen effects as well.

00:33:01.200 --> 00:33:06.360
[Guest 2]: Well, let's say, you know, the Chinese mobile phone companies operating in India, there

00:33:06.360 --> 00:33:10.280
[Guest 2]: are a lot of custom duties are put, and then Chinese mobile phones become expensive, and

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:13.840
[Guest 2]: then people start buying mobile phones made in India, okay.

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:18.840
[Guest 2]: So automatically, that mobile phone being made in India will be expensive than what

00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:21.280
[Guest 2]: is the Chinese mobile phone.

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:25.640
[Guest 2]: So everyone has a sort of a consumption basket, right, I mean, we will not suddenly start

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:26.640
[Guest 2]: to make more money.

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:31.080
[Guest 2]: So, if you're spending more money on a particular product, we'll obviously cut it down on something

00:33:31.080 --> 00:33:32.080
[Guest 2]: else.

00:33:32.080 --> 00:33:37.240
[Guest 2]: So, it may benefit a particular sector and a particular product, but it hurts the overall

00:33:37.240 --> 00:33:38.240
[Amit Varma]: economy.

00:33:38.240 --> 00:33:42.400
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, before I come to Ajay, I'll kind of sum up with the two broad unseen effects

00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:44.320
[Amit Varma]: of protectionism seem to be.

00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:49.120
[Amit Varma]: One of course, is that if I am paying, because of tariffs on foreign products, let's say

00:33:49.120 --> 00:33:53.280
[Amit Varma]: a foreign Chinese widget was available for 20 rupees, I instead, you know, there's a

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:56.720
[Amit Varma]: tariff on that, so I have to buy the Indian product for 25.

00:33:56.720 --> 00:34:00.760
[Amit Varma]: The unseen effect is a five bucks, which I don't have to spend on something else, which

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:05.560
[Amit Varma]: would otherwise have gone into the economy and generated jobs and generated productivity.

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:10.240
[Amit Varma]: And the second unseen effect is also that the Indian firms aren't being forced to compete.

00:34:10.240 --> 00:34:14.120
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, like, you know, if those tariffs were not there, the Indian firms would also

00:34:14.120 --> 00:34:19.560
[Amit Varma]: have to lift their game to be able to provide enough value for money to sell at 20 or whatever

00:34:19.560 --> 00:34:23.320
[Amit Varma]: they have to match and their standard, their quality would go up and the good guys would

00:34:23.320 --> 00:34:24.320
[Amit Varma]: survive.

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:28.920
[Amit Varma]: And that would, in fact, then lift them to do better in the exports market.

00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:30.160
[Guest 2]: And I just add one point.

00:34:30.160 --> 00:34:36.160
[Guest 2]: So, you know, when I was growing up as a kid, during Holi, the water pistols that used to

00:34:36.160 --> 00:34:40.240
[Guest 2]: be available, and if you compare those water pistols with the kind of Chinese made water

00:34:40.240 --> 00:34:45.760
[Guest 2]: pistols that come, I mean, the difference is huge that the product available now is

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:49.120
[Guest 2]: so much better than the rubbish that used to be sold back then.

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:54.080
[Guest 2]: So, ultimately, the benefit is for the consumer, obviously, the producer of those, you know,

00:34:54.080 --> 00:34:58.240
[Amit Varma]: the water pistol, the pichkari has lost out, because he couldn't compete.

00:34:58.240 --> 00:35:03.480
[Amit Varma]: I'm utterly amazed at your recent scrutiny of water pistols, it seems to be the case.

00:35:03.480 --> 00:35:05.160
[Amit Varma]: Why are you examining water pistols?

00:35:05.160 --> 00:35:08.440
[Guest 2]: I'm not, I'm just telling you something.

00:35:08.440 --> 00:35:09.440
[Guest 1]: I second that.

00:35:09.440 --> 00:35:10.440
[Guest 1]: I second that.

00:35:10.440 --> 00:35:14.160
[Guest 1]: When I first went to America, this was one of the things that struck me, the water guns

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:15.160
[Unknown]: were so great.

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:19.800
[Guest 1]: I love those water guns, and today those lovely water guns are ubiquitous in India, there's

00:35:19.800 --> 00:35:20.800
[Guest 1]: no fuss anymore.

00:35:20.800 --> 00:35:24.960
[Amit Varma]: Whereas in the olden days, the water guns in India were just bad.

00:35:24.960 --> 00:35:29.280
[Amit Varma]: To come back to the strategy versus tactics kind of thing, you know, you've written recently

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:32.840
[Amit Varma]: that and I think it's in your book also, I don't remember if it's in your book, but you've

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:37.880
[Amit Varma]: written about it recently, how in the 2000s, Vijay Kelkar and Rakesh Mohan rallied the

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:42.920
[Amit Varma]: Ministry of Finance around the slogan, every time we cut tariffs, our exports go up, stop

00:35:42.920 --> 00:35:47.880
[Amit Varma]: quote, right, which is one of the unseen effects that and which is very counterintuitive to

00:35:47.880 --> 00:35:51.440
[Amit Varma]: people that if you cut tariffs, you will have imports coming in, why should exports go up,

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:55.840
[Amit Varma]: but they force your local guys to be competitive, and so on and so forth.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:36:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of that thinking had come because like you pointed out over the decades from

00:36:00.120 --> 00:36:04.920
[Amit Varma]: the 80s onwards, that intellectual capacity had built up and you actually had people like

00:36:04.920 --> 00:36:06.680
[Amit Varma]: that in positions of power.

00:36:06.680 --> 00:36:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of those insights are counterintuitive.

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:11.760
[Amit Varma]: So you do need people with specific learning and insights.

00:36:11.760 --> 00:36:17.120
[Amit Varma]: You can't, you know, just sort of, and today, it seems that we are, you know, a lot of those

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:21.880
[Amit Varma]: lessons have sort of been reversed in the sort of a lot of measures that these guys

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:26.360
[Amit Varma]: carry out seem populist, and they're intuitive, and they seem to make sense.

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:29.600
[Amit Varma]: But if you understand economics, you know that they have the opposite effect.

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:34.840
[Guest 1]: Similarly, I want to call out Arvind Veermani, who used to have a missionary zeal around

00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:35.840
[Guest 1]: one proposition.

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:40.000
[Guest 1]: Okay, and it seems a little counterintuitive, but it's worth recounting.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:44.440
[Guest 1]: He used to emphasize how important it is that if you're going to have a customs tariff,

00:36:44.440 --> 00:36:49.920
[Guest 1]: just have a single uniform rate, don't have the slightest variation in rates, okay, because

00:36:49.920 --> 00:36:56.480
[Guest 1]: there are huge effective protection rates that can come about from very modest differences

00:36:56.480 --> 00:36:57.480
[Guest 1]: in duties.

00:36:57.480 --> 00:37:02.960
[Guest 1]: Like if you have a 10% duty on crude oil and a 20% duty on petroleum products, it works

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:07.520
[Guest 1]: out that you're actually giving a gigantic effective protection to refineries, and so

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:08.520
[Guest 1]: on.

00:37:08.520 --> 00:37:15.360
[Guest 1]: So, I think many of those people used to appear semi-unhinged when they went around selling

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:21.040
[Guest 1]: the larger community on each of these propositions, and I think that's the kind of passion that

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:22.400
[Guest 1]: it takes.

00:37:22.400 --> 00:37:28.160
[Guest 1]: It takes that certain kind of passion to just get fixated by an idea and to talk about it,

00:37:28.160 --> 00:37:35.400
[Guest 1]: to woo people, to persuade people, and over some years, the giant processes of public

00:37:35.400 --> 00:37:39.640
[Guest 1]: policy start moving in that direction, and we started getting some unification of rates

00:37:39.640 --> 00:37:44.680
[Guest 1]: and the reduction of rate dispersion came into the policy agenda.

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:49.880
[Guest 1]: This stuff is not easy, and it takes a mixture of deep intellectual insights and a certain

00:37:49.880 --> 00:37:56.160
[Guest 1]: selfless willingness to not earn political capital in all transactions.

00:37:56.160 --> 00:37:59.840
[Guest 2]: I mean, the ability to sell economics is not easy.

00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:06.240
[Guest 2]: So, you need to have that deep understanding so that you can explain things in a very simple

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:07.240
[Amit Varma]: way.

00:38:07.240 --> 00:38:08.240
[Amit Varma]: This is why we call you the Shah Rukh Khan of economics.

00:38:08.240 --> 00:38:10.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I don't do policy.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:11.720
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, that's very true.

00:38:11.720 --> 00:38:17.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I mean, there are essentially sort of two kinds of things that, you know,

00:38:17.000 --> 00:38:19.600
[Amit Varma]: we discussed before the show that we'll talk about on the show.

00:38:19.600 --> 00:38:24.640
[Amit Varma]: One is a meta level of thinking about the budget and so on and so forth, the strategy

00:38:24.640 --> 00:38:25.640
[Amit Varma]: as it were.

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:30.040
[Amit Varma]: The other is sort of the level of tactics ki yeh galat kya, wo galat kya, yeh galat

00:38:30.040 --> 00:38:34.200
[Amit Varma]: kya, you know, and Vivek has written more about the latter recently in the around 43

00:38:34.200 --> 00:38:36.880
[Amit Varma]: pieces he's written since the budget came out.

00:38:36.880 --> 00:38:40.280
[Amit Varma]: And you Ajay have written, you know, an excellent piece in Business Standard, which will be

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:44.920
[Amit Varma]: linked from the show notes, though, you know, there's a paywall, but we link it anyway for,

00:38:44.920 --> 00:38:47.460
[Amit Varma]: you know, and encourage people to subscribe.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:50.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'll quote a line from that and ask you to elaborate on that, which is you basically

00:38:50.840 --> 00:38:56.800
[Amit Varma]: said, quote, the budget speech has done well to avoid the calls for a large fiscal expansion

00:38:56.800 --> 00:39:02.760
[Amit Varma]: and propping up GDP growth, turning around economic conditions requires greater strategic

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:07.120
[Amit Varma]: thinking about the relationship between the state and the individual and addressing the

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:12.840
[Amit Varma]: unease of private persons that has manifested itself in private investment, stop quote,

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:17.560
[Amit Varma]: which goes a little bit against, you know, a lot of what the commentary art has been

00:39:17.560 --> 00:39:22.200
[Amit Varma]: saying before the budget is that we need fiscal expansion that we need to somehow boost consumption

00:39:22.200 --> 00:39:23.680
[Amit Varma]: and blah, blah, blah.

00:39:23.680 --> 00:39:25.960
[Amit Varma]: And you've said that no, our problem is more fundamental.

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:28.000
[Guest 1]: So can you elaborate on that?

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:30.840
[Guest 1]: So I'm going to hand wave around some magnitudes.

00:39:30.840 --> 00:39:36.540
[Guest 1]: These are all complicated estimates, and I'm happy to waste a half day on estimation.

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:40.000
[Guest 1]: But right now, please take my word for it on certain broad numbers.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.760
[Guest 1]: My podcast often lasts a half day, but nevermind.

00:39:44.760 --> 00:39:51.800
[Guest 1]: At its peak in about 2007-8, private corporate gross fixed capital formation, which is buzzwords

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:56.200
[Guest 1]: for investment, was about 16% of GDP.

00:39:56.200 --> 00:40:01.320
[Guest 1]: And there's been a decline of about 10 percentage points of GDP.

00:40:01.320 --> 00:40:06.520
[Guest 1]: So the first big ballpark figure to keep in mind is that the decline in private corporate

00:40:06.520 --> 00:40:10.000
[Guest 1]: investment works out to about 10% of GDP.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.320
[Guest 1]: 10% of GDP is a gigantic number.

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:15.160
[Guest 1]: It's a very, very large number.

00:40:15.160 --> 00:40:17.640
[Guest 1]: So you could say, we've got a demand shortfall.

00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:19.520
[Guest 1]: Let's go overcome that.

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:25.640
[Guest 1]: So in some sense, you'd need to do 10% of GDP more by way of government spending as

00:40:25.640 --> 00:40:28.440
[Guest 1]: compared to where we were in 2007-8.

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:29.760
[Guest 1]: Now is that even feasible?

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:32.040
[Guest 1]: Do we have that kind of fiscal capacity?

00:40:32.040 --> 00:40:35.480
[Guest 1]: Do we have that fiscal headroom?

00:40:35.480 --> 00:40:40.400
[Guest 1]: The next ballpark number is that the true state of the union government's fiscal deficit

00:40:40.400 --> 00:40:43.640
[Guest 1]: is presently about 6%.

00:40:43.640 --> 00:40:49.360
[Guest 1]: And under any reasonable conduct of fiscal policy institutions, it is unreasonable to

00:40:49.360 --> 00:40:55.880
[Guest 1]: think of anything more than 1% or at most 2% of a move in a year.

00:40:55.880 --> 00:41:00.400
[Guest 1]: So note that the fiscal stimulus, many people are a little confused on this.

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:05.840
[Guest 1]: The fiscal stimulus, when you go from a 6% deficit to an 8% deficit, is 2%.

00:41:05.840 --> 00:41:10.800
[Guest 1]: It's not like you are adding 8% to demand when you go from 6 to 8.

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:14.160
[Guest 1]: You're adding 2% to demand when you go from 6 to 8%.

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:19.240
[Guest 1]: So it seems to me that these magnitudes are far apart.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:25.160
[Guest 1]: And in fact, I also worry that we will be in a difficult fiscal state if we actually

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:28.980
[Guest 1]: go from a 6% deficit to an 8% deficit.

00:41:28.980 --> 00:41:31.520
[Guest 1]: So I was pleased that the budget does not do such a thing.

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:36.320
[Guest 1]: I think that they've broadly retained the status quo of perhaps being about 6%.

00:41:36.320 --> 00:41:41.400
[Guest 1]: I don't yet know a good analysis of this year's numbers, but perhaps it will be about 6%.

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:45.520
[Guest 1]: It seems to be something similar to what was done last year.

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:50.440
[Guest 1]: And then that takes you to the problem that what is this demand shortfall in the economy

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:52.440
[Guest 1]: and how could you change something?

00:41:52.440 --> 00:41:54.280
[Guest 1]: And I'd say go to the root cause.

00:41:54.280 --> 00:41:59.360
[Guest 1]: The root cause is that private persons have pulled back from investing.

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.600
[Guest 1]: We've gone from 16% to 6%.

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:06.560
[Guest 1]: We've got to go into the heads of those private people and wonder why.

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:15.640
[Guest 1]: So what has changed the optimism, the confidence, the trust of private persons in building businesses

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:20.760
[Guest 1]: in India, in investing in India, in committing financial capital in India?

00:42:20.760 --> 00:42:26.000
[Guest 1]: And that takes you to the relationship between the state and the citizenry.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:32.720
[Guest 1]: That do we have the rule of law environment, do we have a government which can be trusted?

00:42:32.720 --> 00:42:38.200
[Guest 1]: Is there too much business model risk because of a government that interferes without warning

00:42:38.200 --> 00:42:40.080
[Guest 1]: in the working of my business?

00:42:40.080 --> 00:42:48.080
[Guest 1]: Is there too much legal and regulatory risk when you have CBI, SEBI, income tax, SFIO,

00:42:48.080 --> 00:42:50.960
[Guest 1]: ED, dot, dot, dot, prowling at your door?

00:42:50.960 --> 00:42:51.960
[Guest 1]: Okay.

00:42:51.960 --> 00:42:52.960
[Guest 1]: These are the kinds of questions to ask.

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:58.680
[Guest 1]: And as you know, Kelkar and I have written a book on these themes of doing a first principles

00:42:58.680 --> 00:43:06.800
[Guest 1]: understanding of what is appropriate relationship between the government and the resident, and

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:10.920
[Guest 1]: what is going wrong in India about that relationship and how we need to change that.

00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:11.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:16.640
[Amit Varma]: And what also strikes me Ajay, that when you speak about private people feeling confidence

00:43:16.640 --> 00:43:20.800
[Amit Varma]: in the rule of law and in the structure of the state and so on, and it feels to me that's

00:43:20.800 --> 00:43:25.920
[Amit Varma]: also affected because of, you know, I think since 2011, and certainly more recently, what

00:43:25.920 --> 00:43:29.080
[Amit Varma]: people call tax terrorism has just gone up massively.

00:43:29.080 --> 00:43:34.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's been exacerbated by the pressure on the government to increase tax revenues,

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:39.080
[Amit Varma]: because tax revenues, every year, you know, simply don't meet what the expectations of

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:42.360
[Amit Varma]: the government, and that relationship just gets worse and worse.

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:46.560
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, another very interesting stat, which I pointed out in your book is the massive

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:51.040
[Amit Varma]: flight of millionaires over the last few years from the country, and, you know, which is

00:43:51.040 --> 00:43:52.640
[Amit Varma]: indicative of larger problem.

00:43:52.640 --> 00:43:56.120
[Amit Varma]: You can't just say, oh, a few elite, rich riches are leaving the country, let it be,

00:43:56.120 --> 00:43:57.800
[Amit Varma]: but they are leaving for a reason.

00:43:57.800 --> 00:44:02.240
[Amit Varma]: And that's where the job creation and the entrepreneurship and the drive comes from.

00:44:02.240 --> 00:44:05.400
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, that's something that we should worry about.

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:08.960
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, is any cognizance of all of this, that how do you build confidence in

00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:09.960
[Amit Varma]: people?

00:44:09.960 --> 00:44:15.960
[Guest 1]: Well, so this is the frontiers of the Indian economic policy debate.

00:44:15.960 --> 00:44:21.480
[Guest 1]: As you said, many people are thinking around small practical things, like let's raise the

00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:28.440
[Guest 1]: deficit a bit, or let's raise some customs duties a bit, and let's solve the problem

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:30.320
[Guest 1]: of the NBFC sector.

00:44:30.320 --> 00:44:34.520
[Guest 1]: It's no longer a problem that can be addressed in those small ways.

00:44:34.520 --> 00:44:38.400
[Guest 1]: I think it requires going back to the foundation.

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:45.360
[Guest 1]: In the firm data, there is a very interesting story about smaller problems versus larger

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:46.360
[Guest 1]: problems.

00:44:46.360 --> 00:44:55.000
[Guest 1]: In 2013, 14, 14, 15, 15, 16, you see what is called a normal credit profile, that the

00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:00.680
[Guest 1]: firms with high credit risk have pulled back on investment, but the firms with low credit

00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:03.960
[Guest 1]: risk continue to invest significantly.

00:45:03.960 --> 00:45:09.620
[Guest 1]: But from 2017, 18 onwards, you see weak investment by all kinds of firms, whether firm is credit

00:45:09.620 --> 00:45:12.720
[Guest 1]: stressed or not credit stressed, investment has pulled back.

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:14.840
[Guest 1]: So why did it change for the latter category?

00:45:14.840 --> 00:45:20.320
[Guest 1]: I think in that early period, we were in the early stages of the balance sheet crisis,

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:26.720
[Guest 1]: and there was still optimism about how the overall Indian growth story would work out.

00:45:26.720 --> 00:45:28.320
[Guest 1]: But some firms were credit constrained.

00:45:28.320 --> 00:45:33.460
[Guest 1]: The lenders were unwilling to commit to those firms, while other firms were able to continue

00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:34.460
[Guest 1]: to invest.

00:45:34.460 --> 00:45:40.560
[Guest 1]: So that is where we got what I would call a normal credit profile, that there was good

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:46.000
[Guest 1]: investment by the healthy firms, and there was a crimping of investment by the firms

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:47.680
[Guest 1]: with high credit risk.

00:45:47.680 --> 00:45:53.720
[Guest 1]: But in the more recent years, starting from, I seem to remember 2016, 17 or 2017, 18, the

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:54.720
[Guest 1]: profile is gone.

00:45:54.720 --> 00:46:00.960
[Guest 1]: So in all parts of the firm universe, you tend to see weak investment, and it's no longer

00:46:00.960 --> 00:46:02.200
[Guest 1]: become very credit sensitive.

00:46:02.200 --> 00:46:07.540
[Guest 1]: So that is saying something else, even firms who have operating cash are reluctant to invest.

00:46:07.540 --> 00:46:09.800
[Guest 1]: And so that's why you've got to go deeper.

00:46:09.800 --> 00:46:12.280
[Guest 1]: It's not just a matter of rescuing the financial system.

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:18.720
[Guest 1]: It was at that time, in 2013, 14, in 2014, 15, the highest priority for policymakers

00:46:18.720 --> 00:46:23.440
[Guest 1]: should have been to undertake the financial reforms and fix the foundations of the financial

00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:24.440
[Guest 1]: system.

00:46:24.440 --> 00:46:25.720
[Guest 1]: But that opportunity was lost.

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:29.320
[Guest 1]: Today, of course, we should fix the financial system, we should make the financial system

00:46:29.320 --> 00:46:30.400
[Guest 1]: work better.

00:46:30.400 --> 00:46:35.240
[Guest 1]: But today, it's become a bigger and different problem compared to where we were in 2013,

00:46:35.240 --> 00:46:36.240
[Guest 1]: 14, 2014, 15.

00:46:36.240 --> 00:46:41.600
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask you to elaborate on that a little bit, and digress a bit from the budget itself

00:46:41.600 --> 00:46:46.240
[Amit Varma]: and the budget making process itself, where you or Josh Feldman, I don't know which of

00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:52.040
[Amit Varma]: you and I met you once at one of our weekend reading groups, pointed out, use the analogy

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:56.240
[Amit Varma]: of how our credit crisis is like a cancer in our economy.

00:46:56.240 --> 00:47:02.200
[Amit Varma]: It's a root cause, which, you know, is making a lot of the rest of the economy very, very

00:47:02.200 --> 00:47:03.200
[Amit Varma]: sick.

00:47:03.200 --> 00:47:07.120
[Amit Varma]: Is there an understanding of this within the economic policymakers today?

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:11.480
[Amit Varma]: Is there anything in what they are doing, including in this budget that sort of addresses

00:47:11.480 --> 00:47:14.160
[Amit Varma]: that or does that cancer continue to fester?

00:47:14.160 --> 00:47:16.360
[Amit Varma]: And what exactly is that cancer?

00:47:16.360 --> 00:47:26.400
[Guest 1]: The cancer lies in the fact that perhaps half of the banking and NBFC balance sheet is distressed.

00:47:26.400 --> 00:47:30.880
[Guest 1]: Perhaps there are bad assets on the LIC balance sheet.

00:47:30.880 --> 00:47:35.280
[Guest 1]: And LIC is the biggest financial firm in the country today.

00:47:35.280 --> 00:47:41.620
[Guest 1]: And the managers inside these firms know that their firms are not in good shape.

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:44.160
[Guest 1]: And that leads to risk aversion, that leads to caution.

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:46.960
[Guest 1]: So that's the heart and soul of the cancer.

00:47:46.960 --> 00:47:52.800
[Guest 1]: That cancer was, of course, created and aided and enabled by the financial regulators, who

00:47:52.800 --> 00:47:59.680
[Guest 1]: created rules that made it possible for the financial firms to not recognize these problems.

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:07.040
[Guest 1]: So the regulators supported the firms in kicking the can down the road, hoping that there will

00:48:07.040 --> 00:48:11.280
[Guest 1]: be some thing that will happen in the future whereby the problem will magically go away.

00:48:11.280 --> 00:48:14.400
[Guest 1]: And of course, these things don't go away by themselves.

00:48:14.400 --> 00:48:18.740
[Guest 1]: So I feel we're still stuck in a difficult and challenging balance sheet.

00:48:18.740 --> 00:48:25.960
[Guest 1]: But I will emphasize that in the 2016-17 and 2017-18 data, it's surprising how you do not

00:48:25.960 --> 00:48:30.920
[Guest 1]: find a clear linkage between firm credit stress and firm investment.

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:32.480
[Guest 1]: So something bigger is afoot.

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:37.920
[Guest 2]: In fact, this is something that Mahesh Vyas has also been writing about over and over

00:48:37.920 --> 00:48:38.920
[Guest 2]: again.

00:48:38.920 --> 00:48:43.680
[Guest 2]: So I would just like to add, you know, about the regulator point.

00:48:43.680 --> 00:48:45.400
[Guest 2]: And it's very interesting.

00:48:45.400 --> 00:48:50.280
[Guest 2]: So I've just finished writing this, you know, book on the banking crisis.

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:57.880
[Guest 2]: But from whatever I sort of researched, I think the thinking was that as we go along,

00:48:57.880 --> 00:49:04.320
[Guest 2]: the economy will recover, the loan book will grow, and the bad loans will become a very

00:49:04.320 --> 00:49:07.920
[Guest 2]: small proportion of the overall loans.

00:49:07.920 --> 00:49:10.440
[Guest 2]: Now, there are fundamental mistakes here.

00:49:10.440 --> 00:49:15.080
[Guest 2]: Obviously, one was the assumption that the economy will go back to growing at 9% and

00:49:15.080 --> 00:49:17.160
[Guest 2]: all which did not happen.

00:49:17.160 --> 00:49:23.320
[Guest 2]: The second mistake that I guess, was the fact that they hope that they would be able to

00:49:23.320 --> 00:49:26.600
[Guest 2]: control the total amount of bad loans, which also did not happen.

00:49:26.600 --> 00:49:30.360
[Guest 2]: I mean, they kept rising till 2018-19.

00:49:30.360 --> 00:49:32.680
[Guest 2]: Now they are falling because they're being written off.

00:49:32.680 --> 00:49:37.840
[Guest 2]: It's not like, you know, they're able to reclaim the bad loans, actually.

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:43.640
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, and there are some figures I can't kind of get around, like in one of your pieces,

00:49:43.640 --> 00:49:49.200
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned that the amount it's allocated towards recapitalizing is 2 lakh rupees.

00:49:49.200 --> 00:49:52.600
[Guest 2]: But then see what also happens is, so this is very funny, okay.

00:49:52.600 --> 00:49:56.440
[Guest 2]: And this happened in the interim budget that Piyush Goyal presented last year.

00:49:56.440 --> 00:50:02.040
[Guest 2]: The allocation towards recapitalizing public sector banks was rupees 2 lakh.

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:03.960
[Guest 2]: And this year also, it's rupees 2 lakh.

00:50:03.960 --> 00:50:09.400
[Guest 2]: Now, the thing here is that obviously, because we're working through recapitalization bonds,

00:50:09.400 --> 00:50:11.560
[Guest 2]: so this is in a way budget neutral.

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:16.760
[Guest 2]: So essentially, what happens is that the government issues special bonds, the banks buy these

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:21.440
[Guest 2]: bonds, and then the government takes that money to reinvest in the bank itself.

00:50:21.440 --> 00:50:26.440
[Guest 2]: So to that extent, it does not add to the budget, to the fiscal deficit immediately,

00:50:26.440 --> 00:50:30.080
[Guest 2]: though over a period of time it does because the government has to pay interest on these

00:50:30.080 --> 00:50:31.080
[Guest 2]: bonds.

00:50:31.080 --> 00:50:34.360
[Guest 2]: And finally, you know, they need to repay it as well.

00:50:34.360 --> 00:50:37.160
[Guest 2]: So obviously, the public debt goes up.

00:50:37.160 --> 00:50:43.800
[Guest 2]: But the point is that when public sector banks have bad loans worth 7,80,000 crore, there

00:50:43.800 --> 00:50:48.640
[Guest 2]: has to be, you know, some sort of investment that has to be made into them.

00:50:48.640 --> 00:50:53.040
[Guest 2]: And I guess the assumption this time around is that we've sort of the banks have recovered

00:50:53.040 --> 00:50:55.880
[Guest 2]: or probably they want to sell these banks, so which is not very clear.

00:50:55.880 --> 00:51:00.240
[Guest 2]: I mean, the only thing that she said very clearly was, the government will sell the

00:51:00.240 --> 00:51:03.800
[Guest 2]: remaining stake in IDBI to investors.

00:51:03.800 --> 00:51:05.880
[Amit Varma]: This was what was said very, very clearly.

00:51:05.880 --> 00:51:11.440
[Amit Varma]: How would public sector banks be recapitalized, Ajay, like, how does one deal with this problem?

00:51:11.440 --> 00:51:14.800
[Amit Varma]: Because a lot of it to me seems like throwing good money after bad.

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:15.800
[Guest 1]: It's a tough problem.

00:51:15.800 --> 00:51:22.880
[Guest 1]: I remember when Yashwant Sinha was planning that we should reduce the government ownership

00:51:22.880 --> 00:51:25.920
[Guest 1]: in public sector banks from 51% to 33%.

00:51:25.920 --> 00:51:32.580
[Guest 1]: He got quite some pushback, not from the left of center parties, but from within the BJP.

00:51:32.580 --> 00:51:36.440
[Guest 1]: It was BJP MPs who were uncomfortable about the idea.

00:51:36.440 --> 00:51:42.520
[Guest 1]: I think we need a lot more high quality discourse in the country around the meaning of public

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:44.400
[Guest 1]: money.

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:51.560
[Guest 1]: More people need to worry that every one rupee of government expenditure comes at an opportunity

00:51:51.560 --> 00:51:54.280
[Guest 1]: cost of three rupees of GDP.

00:51:54.280 --> 00:52:02.040
[Guest 1]: More people need to worry that for every 10,000 crore rupees, I can build 1,000 crore of expressway.

00:52:02.040 --> 00:52:05.600
[Guest 1]: And is that a better use of money than recapitalizing banks?

00:52:05.600 --> 00:52:11.320
[Guest 1]: So I feel we need to think more about what we do with public money.

00:52:11.320 --> 00:52:19.680
[Guest 1]: If we could be more frugal in our use of public money, I feel the best of all worlds is to

00:52:19.680 --> 00:52:21.960
[Guest 1]: privatize the public sector banks.

00:52:21.960 --> 00:52:27.240
[Guest 1]: Maybe a government might like to hang on to an SBI for some government type functions,

00:52:27.240 --> 00:52:34.560
[Guest 1]: but for the others, it seems feasible that each of them should be put through a big good

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:36.840
[Guest 1]: bank, bad bank operation.

00:52:36.840 --> 00:52:42.880
[Guest 1]: And then the good bank is sold to a private person and the bad bank is liquidated by the

00:52:42.880 --> 00:52:46.360
[Guest 1]: government as was done with UTI.

00:52:46.360 --> 00:52:49.000
[Guest 1]: And I think that will be the best of all worlds.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:56.880
[Guest 1]: I would say in passing that if that is your long range strategy, then it was not very

00:52:56.880 --> 00:53:03.680
[Guest 1]: useful to do these mergers of PSU banks, because it's much better to sell smaller banks.

00:53:03.680 --> 00:53:08.160
[Guest 1]: The better off selling a bank with a 50,000 crore balance sheet or a 1 lakh crore balance

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:13.440
[Guest 1]: sheet, rather than trying to deal with 2 lakh crore, 3 lakh crore of balance sheet.

00:53:13.440 --> 00:53:19.320
[Guest 1]: So this is where a little bit of strategic thinking would have been useful that what's

00:53:19.320 --> 00:53:20.600
[Guest 1]: our long run game plan?

00:53:20.600 --> 00:53:23.480
[Guest 1]: Are we going to have public sector banks forever?

00:53:23.480 --> 00:53:25.560
[Guest 1]: Are we going to privatize public sector banks?

00:53:25.560 --> 00:53:29.600
[Guest 1]: If our long game was that we're going to privatize public sector banks, and we should have never

00:53:29.600 --> 00:53:30.960
[Amit Varma]: done these mergers.

00:53:30.960 --> 00:53:31.960
[Amit Varma]: Is it a long game?

00:53:31.960 --> 00:53:33.880
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm not saying do you agree with the long game or not?

00:53:33.880 --> 00:53:36.200
[Amit Varma]: But do these people have any long game thinking at all?

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:39.080
[Amit Varma]: Or is it sort of all very ad hoc?

00:53:39.080 --> 00:53:44.200
[Guest 1]: My understanding is that the current mainstream view of the long game is that there is no

00:53:44.200 --> 00:53:48.880
[Guest 1]: problem and that incremental fixes will suffice.

00:53:48.880 --> 00:53:56.800
[Guest 1]: But public sector banks did badly because of a few corrupt individuals and industrialists.

00:53:56.800 --> 00:53:59.520
[Guest 1]: And we will appoint better people and the problems will end.

00:53:59.520 --> 00:54:01.920
[Guest 1]: This is the mainstream view.

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:02.920
[Guest 1]: And I happen to disagree.

00:54:02.920 --> 00:54:05.840
[Guest 1]: But this is my reading of where the mainstream stands.

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:06.840
[Amit Varma]: And it's a classic fallacy.

00:54:06.840 --> 00:54:09.920
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, this is totally true.

00:54:09.920 --> 00:54:12.240
[Guest 2]: And I'll sort of admit something here.

00:54:12.240 --> 00:54:16.240
[Guest 2]: Five, six years back, I was also of the view that you know, all these cronies have sort

00:54:16.240 --> 00:54:19.780
[Guest 2]: of taken our money and all that from public sector banks.

00:54:19.780 --> 00:54:24.040
[Guest 2]: But you know, having sort of written a longish document on it now and research the topic

00:54:24.040 --> 00:54:27.480
[Guest 2]: a little better, I think obviously there are crony capitalists involved.

00:54:27.480 --> 00:54:28.800
[Guest 2]: I mean, you can't deny that.

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:30.160
[Guest 2]: But that was not the only reason.

00:54:30.160 --> 00:54:34.880
[Guest 2]: I mean, there were a lot of businesses just simply went overboard borrowing as well.

00:54:34.880 --> 00:54:37.960
[Guest 2]: Having said that, you know, this is where it gets very interesting.

00:54:37.960 --> 00:54:45.240
[Guest 2]: A lot of people, and this includes our policymakers, and I'll give an example here, believe, continue

00:54:45.240 --> 00:54:49.680
[Guest 2]: to believe that public sector banks are the ones driving banking in this country, which

00:54:49.680 --> 00:54:51.600
[Guest 2]: is absolute rubbish.

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:56.960
[Guest 2]: So if you look at this year's economic survey, the economic survey quotes that public sector

00:54:56.960 --> 00:55:03.240
[Guest 2]: banks have 70% market share in Indian banking, which is rubbish of the highest order.

00:55:03.240 --> 00:55:10.000
[Guest 2]: Because if you look at RBI data, as of September 30, public sector banks have 58% of the credit

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:12.200
[Guest 2]: and 62% of the deposits.

00:55:12.200 --> 00:55:15.680
[Guest 2]: And this has been falling from the last five years, six years.

00:55:15.680 --> 00:55:22.440
[Guest 2]: The deposits had peaked at around 75%, and the credit had peaked at around 72, 71%.

00:55:22.440 --> 00:55:25.200
[Guest 2]: From that 72%, it's already fallen to 58.

00:55:25.200 --> 00:55:26.200
[Guest 2]: What does this mean?

00:55:26.200 --> 00:55:30.840
[Guest 2]: This essentially means that even though the government doesn't want to privatize these

00:55:30.840 --> 00:55:35.280
[Guest 2]: banks, the banking sector is getting privatized on its own.

00:55:35.280 --> 00:55:40.640
[Guest 2]: And a lot of these private banks are now attacking public sector banks directly.

00:55:40.640 --> 00:55:45.600
[Guest 2]: You know, they go around, they go to depositors' homes, get their deposits transferred.

00:55:45.600 --> 00:55:46.600
[Guest 2]: So all that is happening.

00:55:46.600 --> 00:55:52.760
[Guest 2]: I mean, imagine the economic survey making a mistake as drastic as this, wherein the

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:55.800
[Guest 2]: share has fallen from 72 to 58%.

00:55:55.800 --> 00:55:57.400
[Guest 2]: And you are still stuck at 70%.

00:55:57.400 --> 00:56:03.520
[Guest 2]: I mean, 58% can be rounded off to 60%, it can be rounded off to 70%.

00:56:03.520 --> 00:56:09.520
[Guest 2]: So in their heads, they're still, you know, ki bhai SBI hai aur, but then that's not true.

00:56:09.520 --> 00:56:13.840
[Guest 2]: And you know, what is also happening is that the younger Indian does not want to deal with

00:56:13.840 --> 00:56:15.920
[Guest 2]: these older banks.

00:56:15.920 --> 00:56:21.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, when was the last time you heard, you know, a 30-year-old or a 25-year-old actually

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:22.000
[Guest 2]: went to a bank?

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:25.360
[Guest 2]: I mean, they like to do their banking online.

00:56:25.360 --> 00:56:29.640
[Guest 2]: And the online banking systems of private banks are much, much better than some of these

00:56:29.640 --> 00:56:30.640
[Guest 2]: public sector banks.

00:56:30.640 --> 00:56:31.640
[Guest 1]: So...

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:32.640
[Guest 1]: So Vivek, I agree with you.

00:56:32.640 --> 00:56:35.680
[Guest 1]: And I make an analogy with MTNL and BSNL.

00:56:35.680 --> 00:56:38.480
[Guest 1]: You've privatized BSNL, great.

00:56:38.480 --> 00:56:42.240
[Guest 1]: The government did not privatize MTNL and BSNL.

00:56:42.240 --> 00:56:46.760
[Guest 1]: But by and large, it's irrelevant, because the business of telecom is gone, turned into

00:56:46.760 --> 00:56:48.480
[Guest 1]: a private sector character.

00:56:48.480 --> 00:56:52.800
[Guest 1]: And the resources are increasingly controlled by private persons.

00:56:52.800 --> 00:56:58.960
[Guest 1]: And you know, we are today surrounded by firms like Jio and Airtel and ACT and so on.

00:56:58.960 --> 00:57:01.440
[Guest 1]: And these are the telecom firms of India today.

00:57:01.440 --> 00:57:04.200
[Guest 1]: So in similar fashion, that is a transformation happening in banking.

00:57:04.200 --> 00:57:05.200
[Guest 1]: Or Air India for that matter.

00:57:05.200 --> 00:57:14.080
[Guest 1]: But I do want to call an alarm on the distinction between airlines and telecom versus banking.

00:57:14.080 --> 00:57:21.600
[Guest 1]: That in telecom or in airlines, we don't really mourn the transformation away from Air India

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:28.160
[Guest 1]: in favor of, you know, I was about to say jet airways, which we had in the episode.

00:57:28.160 --> 00:57:33.200
[Guest 1]: But in the case of banking, there is a fundamental problem, which is that there is an old saying

00:57:33.200 --> 00:57:39.480
[Guest 1]: amongst economists, the one thing worse than a public sector bank is a badly regulated

00:57:39.480 --> 00:57:41.080
[Guest 1]: private sector bank.

00:57:41.080 --> 00:57:48.680
[Guest 1]: So when the regulatory capacity is weak, private bankers will be rapacious and extract the

00:57:48.680 --> 00:57:54.600
[Guest 1]: maximal personal benefits that they can out of every glitch in the regulations.

00:57:54.600 --> 00:58:00.120
[Guest 1]: So if one could strategize this correctly, the right sequencing in which to do this is

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:05.600
[Guest 1]: to first undertake the required RBI reforms to build capability at RBI.

00:58:05.600 --> 00:58:12.240
[Guest 1]: Because ultimately, RBI was the one on the watch as the entire banking difficulty unfolded

00:58:12.240 --> 00:58:13.240
[Guest 1]: over the last...

00:58:13.240 --> 00:58:14.240
[Guest 1]: Slipped on the watch.

00:58:14.240 --> 00:58:15.240
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:58:15.240 --> 00:58:20.880
[Guest 1]: And so we do need to recognize that there were failures of concepts and principles and

00:58:20.880 --> 00:58:27.200
[Guest 1]: intellectual frameworks and regulations and of course, the implementation of those regulations.

00:58:27.200 --> 00:58:35.120
[Guest 1]: And we need to fix that before we confront large complex private banks who will be hard

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:40.520
[Guest 1]: driving in achieving million dollar bonuses for individuals inside those banks.

00:58:40.520 --> 00:58:44.280
[Guest 2]: In fact, talking about RBI and bad loans.

00:58:44.280 --> 00:58:51.240
[Guest 2]: So after Governor Subbarao retired, he wrote this lovely little book on central banking.

00:58:51.240 --> 00:58:56.600
[Guest 2]: And the interesting thing is that the term NPAs or bad loans aren't even used once in

00:58:56.600 --> 00:58:58.040
[Guest 2]: the entire book.

00:58:58.040 --> 00:59:01.320
[Guest 2]: And he was the governor from 2008 to 2013.

00:59:01.320 --> 00:59:06.560
[Guest 2]: And most of the crisis unfolded between, I would say, 2010, 11, 12, and 13.

00:59:06.560 --> 00:59:11.280
[Guest 2]: So that tells you as to where the attention, the focus of RBI was during those years.

00:59:11.280 --> 00:59:16.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, I can understand 2008, 2009, given the financial crisis and everything else.

00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:21.960
[Guest 2]: But for the remaining four years, when the crisis unfolded, there had to be something

00:59:21.960 --> 00:59:24.120
[Guest 2]: that would have happened at the bank.

00:59:24.120 --> 00:59:25.120
[Amit Varma]: So clearly...

00:59:25.120 --> 00:59:29.960
[Amit Varma]: So, before we go in for a commercial break, three quick responses to what you guys just

00:59:29.960 --> 00:59:35.800
[Amit Varma]: said and I think it's perhaps a subject for another episode on regulation and why banking

00:59:35.800 --> 00:59:36.800
[Amit Varma]: is so different.

00:59:36.800 --> 00:59:41.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, my tendency to view markets is that I think competition is the best regulation

00:59:41.840 --> 00:59:44.760
[Amit Varma]: that you need the state to provide a firm rule of law.

00:59:44.760 --> 00:59:49.640
[Amit Varma]: But beyond that, any regulation will tend or even the custom of being able to regulate

00:59:49.640 --> 00:59:53.200
[Amit Varma]: will support some interest group that the benefit of the other competition is always

00:59:53.200 --> 00:59:54.200
[Amit Varma]: the best regulator.

00:59:54.200 --> 00:59:58.760
[Amit Varma]: So if you can ensure easy entry and competition, that takes care of a lot of those problems.

00:59:58.760 --> 01:00:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And I know you'll have, you know, certain caveats to that and we can discuss that some

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:04.000
[Amit Varma]: other day.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:08.800
[Amit Varma]: Secondly, I like the way Vivek that you characterized the privatization of banking where you're

01:00:08.800 --> 01:00:13.680
[Amit Varma]: saying that even if public sector banks aren't being privatized, banking itself is.

01:00:13.680 --> 01:00:18.640
[Amit Varma]: And the analogy you do of, you know, telecom and airlines is to me very accurate.

01:00:18.640 --> 01:00:22.320
[Amit Varma]: That's what I always say that if you know, I remember how they were government monopolies

01:00:22.320 --> 01:00:25.520
[Amit Varma]: in the 80s, and you had to wait five years to get a phone and blah, blah, blah.

01:00:25.520 --> 01:00:27.720
[Guest 2]: And I'll give you an example here.

01:00:27.720 --> 01:00:35.760
[Guest 2]: So I still remember 1987-88, my father, who was a public sector employee, we took an LTC.

01:00:35.760 --> 01:00:39.240
[Guest 2]: And it was the first time I think he was entitled for air travel.

01:00:39.240 --> 01:00:43.320
[Guest 2]: And we went to Srinagar, which was hometown and we came back.

01:00:43.320 --> 01:00:48.200
[Guest 2]: The total money we paid in Indian Airlines back then, from what he told me, and I remember

01:00:48.200 --> 01:00:52.360
[Guest 2]: was 75,000 rupees back in the mid 80s.

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:57.680
[Guest 2]: 75,000 bucks, I mean, obviously, he didn't pay it, the company did.

01:00:57.680 --> 01:01:02.640
[Guest 2]: But imagine, I mean, from that, I mean, even now, it would probably be the same amount

01:01:02.640 --> 01:01:03.640
[Amit Varma]: for four people.

01:01:03.640 --> 01:01:04.640
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:01:04.640 --> 01:01:07.520
[Amit Varma]: And if you just allow private participation in a lot of these areas, you'll soon find

01:01:07.520 --> 01:01:10.240
[Amit Varma]: that government participation will become redundant.

01:01:10.240 --> 01:01:11.320
[Amit Varma]: And the government should.

01:01:11.320 --> 01:01:14.520
[Amit Varma]: And before we go into a break, the final point is, you know, I just wanted to point out the

01:01:14.520 --> 01:01:18.840
[Amit Varma]: fallacy that you pointed out in this case, that people think that, oh, if we just put

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:22.680
[Amit Varma]: the right individuals in charge, it's okay, things will become better.

01:01:22.680 --> 01:01:26.720
[Amit Varma]: It's a question of having good people running these things is a classic fallacy, which has

01:01:26.720 --> 01:01:32.080
[Amit Varma]: ailed not just economic policy thinking, but also politics in India, where what really

01:01:32.080 --> 01:01:37.120
[Amit Varma]: matters is you have institutions, you have good rules of the game in terms of the Constitution,

01:01:37.120 --> 01:01:39.720
[Amit Varma]: and so on, which have good restraints on power.

01:01:39.720 --> 01:01:46.200
[Amit Varma]: And what I keep saying is that you should have a system whereby even if the most murderous

01:01:46.200 --> 01:01:50.960
[Amit Varma]: sociopath rises to power, he can't do much damage because of the way the rules of the

01:01:50.960 --> 01:01:51.960
[Amit Varma]: game are.

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:57.680
[Amit Varma]: And we think too little in terms of institutions and too much in terms of individuals on which

01:01:57.680 --> 01:01:58.960
[Amit Varma]: note we can go into a break.

01:01:58.960 --> 01:02:01.960
[Guest 2]: Okay, I just want to take one of Ajay's points forward.

01:02:01.960 --> 01:02:07.520
[Guest 2]: So you know, so on this thing of privatizing public sector banks, I don't what I don't

01:02:07.520 --> 01:02:12.360
[Guest 2]: get is, I mean, I can understand you want to hang on to an SBI or a Bank of Baroda or

01:02:12.360 --> 01:02:14.960
[Guest 2]: a Punjab National Bank or a Canara Bank.

01:02:14.960 --> 01:02:18.760
[Guest 2]: What I don't get is why do you want to hang on to an Indian Overseas Bank, a Yuko Bank,

01:02:18.760 --> 01:02:24.080
[Guest 2]: a United Bank, a Central Bank, a Bank of Maharashtra for that matter, a Punjab and Sindh Bank.

01:02:24.080 --> 01:02:27.600
[Guest 2]: So if you look at their, you know, the books of these banks, most of them are like riddled

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:28.600
[Guest 2]: with bad loans.

01:02:28.600 --> 01:02:34.480
[Guest 2]: But even that apart, the total amount of credit or loans that they've given out are miniscule

01:02:34.480 --> 01:02:37.860
[Guest 2]: in proportion to the overall size of banking in India.

01:02:37.860 --> 01:02:42.080
[Guest 2]: So forget, I mean, I mean, we can sell them if there are buyers, but if there are no buyers,

01:02:42.080 --> 01:02:44.000
[Guest 2]: you can simply shut them down.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:50.520
[Guest 2]: I mean, even that is a solution because that's going to sort of, you know, benefit the economy

01:02:50.520 --> 01:02:51.520
[Guest 2]: quite a lot.

01:02:51.520 --> 01:02:54.720
[Guest 2]: So it's just about so it's just, you know, at the end of the day, it's nuisance value

01:02:54.720 --> 01:03:00.240
[Guest 2]: because there are people working there and a few lakh, I mean, the interesting thing

01:03:00.240 --> 01:03:04.960
[Guest 2]: is there's a data point in this time the economic survey, which gives you that the total number

01:03:04.960 --> 01:03:09.120
[Guest 2]: of employees in public sector banks in India are less than 9 lakh.

01:03:09.120 --> 01:03:12.840
[Guest 2]: So if you take these smaller banks, the total number of employees would at best be one and

01:03:12.840 --> 01:03:14.160
[Guest 2]: a half, one, one and a half.

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:20.160
[Guest 2]: So for one, one and a half lakh people in a population of 130 crore, why do you have

01:03:20.160 --> 01:03:22.400
[Guest 2]: to take a bad solution?

01:03:22.400 --> 01:03:24.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, take the good solution and implement it.

01:03:24.080 --> 01:03:28.960
[Amit Varma]: And what you see is the benefit of the status quo on these 9 lakh people, which is a concentrated

01:03:28.960 --> 01:03:33.200
[Amit Varma]: but not the diffuse costs on all the rest of us.

01:03:33.200 --> 01:03:34.200
[Guest 2]: Not just of...

01:03:34.200 --> 01:03:35.200
[Guest 2]: Because the rest of us don't realize.

01:03:35.200 --> 01:03:39.800
[Amit Varma]: The rest of us don't realize because we should, we all need a break.

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:41.960
[Amit Varma]: The citizens of this nation need a break.

01:03:41.960 --> 01:03:45.480
[Amit Varma]: So we'll take a quick commercial break and then all the citizens of the nation can continue

01:03:45.480 --> 01:03:49.600
[Amit Varma]: listening to the scene and the unseen.

