[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen.

01:05:01.720 --> 01:05:07.720
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Ajay Shah and Vivek Kaul, Shah Rukh Khan and Shyam Banegal about cinema

01:05:07.720 --> 01:05:08.720
[Amit Varma]: respectively.

01:05:08.720 --> 01:05:12.360
[Amit Varma]: Vivek is looking most upset at that.

01:05:12.360 --> 01:05:13.360
[Amit Varma]: Why should you be upset?

01:05:13.360 --> 01:05:14.360
[Amit Varma]: He should be upset.

01:05:14.360 --> 01:05:15.360
[Amit Varma]: You're Shah Rukh Khan.

01:05:15.360 --> 01:05:16.360
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm not.

01:05:16.360 --> 01:05:17.360
[Amit Varma]: You're not.

01:05:17.360 --> 01:05:20.720
[Amit Varma]: I just want to kind of sort of get back to the budget and you know, to carry on from

01:05:20.720 --> 01:05:25.080
[Amit Varma]: what I was sort of the note I ended on just before the break is that and a point that

01:05:25.080 --> 01:05:29.840
[Amit Varma]: you have also made very eloquently many times Ajay that you know, the problem is not that

01:05:29.840 --> 01:05:34.560
[Amit Varma]: we no longer have good individuals who are sort of making the right decisions.

01:05:34.560 --> 01:05:40.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, there are individuals in of the 90s in the early 2000s, who are now semi legends

01:05:40.200 --> 01:05:43.480
[Amit Varma]: within the community like Mr. Kilker, Rakesh Mohan and so on.

01:05:43.480 --> 01:05:44.480
[Amit Varma]: And they're not there.

01:05:44.480 --> 01:05:45.960
[Amit Varma]: But that's not the problem as far as I can see it.

01:05:45.960 --> 01:05:50.920
[Amit Varma]: The way it seems to me is that the problem rather is that somewhere the incentives have

01:05:50.920 --> 01:05:55.720
[Amit Varma]: gone wrong, that somewhere, the individuals who are there are not thinking like that,

01:05:55.720 --> 01:06:00.580
[Amit Varma]: because there is no need to because the pulls and pressures on them are very different.

01:06:00.580 --> 01:06:05.000
[Amit Varma]: So how would like leaving I don't want you to comment on the specific dispensation right

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:10.280
[Amit Varma]: now leave that aside that is for enters like me, but just at a structural level, how would

01:06:10.280 --> 01:06:11.880
[Amit Varma]: you reform the system?

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:14.640
[Amit Varma]: So you have the right kind of thinking emerges.

01:06:14.640 --> 01:06:20.240
[Guest 1]: You're squarely on track that we should not personalize these discussions.

01:06:20.240 --> 01:06:25.360
[Guest 1]: As Charles de Gaulle said, the graveyards are filled with indispensable men.

01:06:25.360 --> 01:06:31.880
[Guest 1]: So I'm not fussed about individuals, but we should ask the question of incentives.

01:06:31.880 --> 01:06:37.560
[Guest 1]: How do we create conditions under which various elements of economic policymaking deliver

01:06:37.560 --> 01:06:39.000
[Guest 1]: reasonably good outcomes?

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:45.120
[Guest 1]: How do we take a more dispassionate process perspective to the role of these various pieces

01:06:45.120 --> 01:06:46.840
[Guest 1]: of the Indian state?

01:06:46.840 --> 01:06:50.720
[Guest 1]: Finally, individuals inside each of these organizations will look out for themselves

01:06:50.720 --> 01:06:52.260
[Guest 1]: will pursue their own self-interest.

01:06:52.260 --> 01:06:59.080
[Guest 1]: So we should not expect anything more of a line employee of a Ministry of Power or Ministry

01:06:59.080 --> 01:07:08.200
[Guest 1]: of Civil Aviation, or a DEA or a DFS or RBI or SEBI other than to pursue their own interest.

01:07:08.200 --> 01:07:11.880
[Guest 1]: What we should do is think about their role, their function, their accountability, their

01:07:11.880 --> 01:07:13.880
[Guest 1]: checks and balances.

01:07:13.880 --> 01:07:21.920
[Guest 1]: And it requires that kind of more dispassionate, little bit of detached perspective on analyzing

01:07:21.920 --> 01:07:27.240
[Guest 1]: these institutions, modifying the rules of the game and the check and balance.

01:07:27.240 --> 01:07:32.960
[Guest 1]: So as to create incentives for regular guys to produce superhuman performance.

01:07:32.960 --> 01:07:37.740
[Guest 1]: I think that's where we have to go in terms of the economic policy reform.

01:07:37.740 --> 01:07:42.320
[Amit Varma]: In the sense, not let nobility and excellence be happenstance, but actually allow for it

01:07:42.320 --> 01:07:45.280
[Amit Varma]: to be manufactured by design.

01:07:45.280 --> 01:07:46.880
[Guest 1]: Does that happen in any government in the world?

01:07:46.880 --> 01:07:47.880
[Guest 1]: Oh, yes.

01:07:47.880 --> 01:07:52.080
[Guest 1]: So I have been a frequent admirer of, for example, the UK Treasury.

01:07:52.080 --> 01:07:54.680
[Guest 1]: The UK Treasury is a remarkable institution.

01:07:54.680 --> 01:07:56.840
[Guest 1]: People come, people go, it's an institution.

01:07:56.840 --> 01:08:02.600
[Guest 1]: It's a formal machine that knows how to think about economics, about budgets.

01:08:02.600 --> 01:08:03.920
[Amit Varma]: And so yeah, this can be done.

01:08:03.920 --> 01:08:04.920
[Amit Varma]: What is different there?

01:08:04.920 --> 01:08:06.800
[Amit Varma]: What have they got right that we haven't?

01:08:06.800 --> 01:08:09.480
[Amit Varma]: Why do those institutional incentives, how are they different?

01:08:09.480 --> 01:08:13.920
[Amit Varma]: How do they sustain themselves there and not fall prey to the pressures of everyday electoral

01:08:13.920 --> 01:08:14.920
[Guest 1]: politics?

01:08:14.920 --> 01:08:21.840
[Guest 1]: So to take an example about tax policy that I just mentioned, there is a tax administration

01:08:21.840 --> 01:08:28.800
[Guest 1]: element of the UK, which is called Her Majesty's, I'm trying to remember the name of the agency,

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:32.800
[Guest 1]: Her Majesty's Customs and Revenues or some such thing.

01:08:32.800 --> 01:08:36.880
[Guest 1]: And they are the tax administrators and they collect taxes from individuals all over the

01:08:36.880 --> 01:08:37.880
[Guest 1]: country.

01:08:37.880 --> 01:08:44.400
[Guest 1]: They're kept at arm's length from the Treasury because you don't want the concept of the

01:08:44.400 --> 01:08:48.800
[Guest 1]: political party in power inflicting income tax rates on their enemies.

01:08:48.800 --> 01:08:58.080
[Guest 1]: So there's a very formal institutional apparatus to firewall the tax administrator from the

01:08:58.080 --> 01:08:59.420
[Guest 1]: political process.

01:08:59.420 --> 01:09:03.480
[Guest 1]: But then back to back with that, you need to construct tremendous amount of check and

01:09:03.480 --> 01:09:06.920
[Guest 1]: balance so that that does not become a law unto itself.

01:09:06.920 --> 01:09:12.800
[Guest 1]: So when we say independence for CBI or independence for RBI, that can very easily turn into officials

01:09:12.800 --> 01:09:17.840
[Guest 1]: pursuing their own self-interest, which is probably worse than having them under political

01:09:17.840 --> 01:09:19.400
[Guest 1]: control.

01:09:19.400 --> 01:09:23.980
[Guest 1]: Then in the UK, the entire control of tax policy is only with the Treasury.

01:09:23.980 --> 01:09:28.520
[Guest 1]: So it is only the equivalent of DEA that writes the tax policy.

01:09:28.520 --> 01:09:33.160
[Guest 1]: So these are examples of formal rules and procedures that create the correct incentives

01:09:33.160 --> 01:09:35.200
[Guest 1]: and then we get the better outcomes.

01:09:35.200 --> 01:09:38.240
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, when the framers of our constitution were writing the constitution

01:09:38.240 --> 01:09:42.960
[Amit Varma]: or when the early rules of the game were being set, obviously, you can't expect them to get

01:09:42.960 --> 01:09:46.800
[Amit Varma]: into such granularity on how specific ministries will function.

01:09:46.800 --> 01:09:48.320
[Amit Varma]: We need these rules today.

01:09:48.320 --> 01:09:51.620
[Amit Varma]: These tools presumably evolved over a period of time in England.

01:09:51.620 --> 01:09:56.720
[Amit Varma]: What would be the sort of impetus for the politicians in charge to actually now build

01:09:56.720 --> 01:10:00.160
[Amit Varma]: these checks and balances because it's in their interest to have the tax department

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:01.160
[Amit Varma]: under them, right?

01:10:01.160 --> 01:10:02.160
[Amit Varma]: Why would they give that away?

01:10:02.160 --> 01:10:10.440
[Guest 1]: So in the 70s and the 80s, we had some reasonably bad ideas in economic policy and it led to

01:10:10.440 --> 01:10:14.960
[Guest 1]: the Hindu rate of growth and to balance of payment crises.

01:10:14.960 --> 01:10:21.880
[Guest 1]: And that did give ample incentive to the politicians that business as usual is not working.

01:10:21.880 --> 01:10:26.600
[Guest 1]: So in similar fashion, I think that men and nations will do the right thing after trying

01:10:26.600 --> 01:10:28.920
[Guest 1]: every reasonable alternative.

01:10:28.920 --> 01:10:36.720
[Guest 1]: And I think that a poor economic performance from 2011 onwards has got the pot on boil.

01:10:36.720 --> 01:10:40.720
[Guest 1]: More and more people are curiously wondering where did we go wrong?

01:10:40.720 --> 01:10:42.200
[Guest 1]: What gives?

01:10:42.200 --> 01:10:44.160
[Guest 1]: And all of us are part of that discussion.

01:10:44.160 --> 01:10:51.760
[Guest 1]: And I think that enough of the Indian intelligentsia is able to understand these problems and agree

01:10:51.760 --> 01:10:54.440
[Guest 1]: on an approach on how to do this.

01:10:54.440 --> 01:10:55.440
[Guest 1]: Then things will change.

01:10:55.440 --> 01:11:00.120
[Guest 1]: I want to give you one last example about this kind of work.

01:11:00.120 --> 01:11:08.200
[Guest 1]: In 2003, when Jaswant Singh was finance minister, he asked Vijay Kelkar to lead a team, which

01:11:08.200 --> 01:11:11.320
[Guest 1]: was titled the Ministry of Finance for the 21st century.

01:11:11.320 --> 01:11:12.320
[Guest 1]: Okay.

01:11:12.320 --> 01:11:15.820
[Guest 1]: Now this is an incredibly important problem because the Indian Ministry of Finance is

01:11:15.820 --> 01:11:18.840
[Guest 1]: frankly a 1960s institution.

01:11:18.840 --> 01:11:24.800
[Guest 1]: It has not been thought through in these ways about organization, organization design processes,

01:11:24.800 --> 01:11:27.280
[Guest 1]: incentives, check and balance information.

01:11:27.280 --> 01:11:33.720
[Guest 1]: These foundational things have never been done differently since the 60s and the 70s.

01:11:33.720 --> 01:11:40.920
[Guest 1]: So in 2003, Jaswant Singh said that we need a Ministry of Finance that is commensurate

01:11:40.920 --> 01:11:46.560
[Guest 1]: with the complexities of what India is today and where we are going for the next 25 years.

01:11:46.560 --> 01:11:51.840
[Guest 1]: And Vijay Kelkar led a team which had some remarkable people who worked on that.

01:11:51.840 --> 01:11:57.120
[Guest 1]: And that report was presented to Mr. Chidambaram, who unfortunately ignored it completely.

01:11:57.120 --> 01:12:00.840
[Guest 1]: But I think that that report is an example of the kind of work that is required.

01:12:00.840 --> 01:12:02.880
[Guest 1]: Is it available in the public domain?

01:12:02.880 --> 01:12:05.960
[Guest 1]: It was unfortunately never put up on the Ministry of Finance website.

01:12:05.960 --> 01:12:10.920
[Guest 1]: So it's a little bit of the black art of Indian economic policy to know these things.

01:12:10.920 --> 01:12:14.400
[Guest 1]: Periodically, people ask me what were the key ideas of that report.

01:12:14.400 --> 01:12:18.720
[Guest 1]: Every one or two years, I get asked for what were the key insights of that report.

01:12:18.720 --> 01:12:22.400
[Guest 1]: So I think it's lurking in the imagination of people, but it's not officially in the

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:23.400
[Guest 1]: public domain.

01:12:23.400 --> 01:12:26.120
[Guest 1]: One should send in an RTI request to obtain a copy.

01:12:26.120 --> 01:12:29.720
[Amit Varma]: If Saket Gokhale is listening to this, kindly put an RTI for this.

01:12:29.720 --> 01:12:34.800
[Amit Varma]: This also matters because economics has, as I keep saying, humanitarian consequences.

01:12:34.800 --> 01:12:40.680
[Amit Varma]: So before we go to the specifics of this budget, my big takeaway from the meta is that all

01:12:40.680 --> 01:12:43.760
[Amit Varma]: of us are afraid that things are going to get worse.

01:12:43.760 --> 01:12:47.480
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps we should hope that things get worse because only a crisis seems to provoke the

01:12:47.480 --> 01:12:53.760
[Amit Varma]: kind of deeper thinking and action that is sort of required in that case.

01:12:53.760 --> 01:12:54.760
[Amit Varma]: Would you agree with that?

01:12:54.760 --> 01:12:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Even though you have previously said in this episode that we overstate the importance of

01:12:57.760 --> 01:12:58.760
[Guest 1]: crisis.

01:12:58.760 --> 01:13:02.280
[Guest 1]: I worry that we have to lay the groundwork of the thoughts, the concepts, the frameworks

01:13:02.280 --> 01:13:08.400
[Guest 1]: about what you would like to do different in the Indian economic policy problem.

01:13:08.400 --> 01:13:10.360
[Guest 1]: There is a lack of knowledge in this field.

01:13:10.360 --> 01:13:13.240
[Guest 1]: There is a lack of an elite consensus in this field.

01:13:13.240 --> 01:13:14.960
[Guest 1]: There is a lack of community.

01:13:14.960 --> 01:13:17.680
[Guest 1]: There is a lack of people that understand these things.

01:13:17.680 --> 01:13:23.680
[Guest 1]: So I think now is the time for thinking and discussion and cogitation, the development

01:13:23.680 --> 01:13:30.960
[Guest 1]: of people, the development of community, so that when there are politicians asking to

01:13:30.960 --> 01:13:36.300
[Guest 1]: do things differently, then there is a body of knowledge and a community that is able

01:13:36.300 --> 01:13:38.000
[Guest 1]: to carry these things forward.

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:41.800
[Guest 1]: Something commensurate to the initial conditions of 1991.

01:13:41.800 --> 01:13:45.840
[Amit Varma]: And I would really hope that the young lady who is going to be finance secretary in the

01:13:45.840 --> 01:13:51.000
[Amit Varma]: year 2045 is taking copious notes as she listens to this episode.

01:13:51.000 --> 01:13:57.000
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, sort of moving on to you and your favorite company, which actually seems to your favorite

01:13:57.000 --> 01:13:58.640
[Amit Varma]: company, of course, LIC.

01:13:58.640 --> 01:14:04.080
[Amit Varma]: And that seems to illustrate what you were saying, you know what you often keep saying

01:14:04.080 --> 01:14:07.120
[Amit Varma]: and it's true of this budget that it looks like different parts of it have been written

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:08.880
[Amit Varma]: by different people.

01:14:08.880 --> 01:14:12.520
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the proposed LIC sale seems to be, sorry.

01:14:12.520 --> 01:14:14.520
[Guest 1]: Amit, it's more than that.

01:14:14.520 --> 01:14:17.720
[Guest 1]: Not only have different parts been written by different people, they've also been typeset

01:14:17.720 --> 01:14:18.720
[Amit Varma]: in different fonts.

01:14:18.720 --> 01:14:19.720
[Amit Varma]: Oh, really?

01:14:19.720 --> 01:14:20.720
[Amit Varma]: In the budget?

01:14:20.720 --> 01:14:21.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:14:21.720 --> 01:14:22.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:14:22.720 --> 01:14:24.440
[Amit Varma]: The other thing I was wondering was that, you know, again, to take a digression, Vivek,

01:14:24.440 --> 01:14:26.400
[Amit Varma]: you pointed out that is some 18,900 words.

01:14:26.400 --> 01:14:27.400
[Guest 2]: 1971 words.

01:14:27.400 --> 01:14:28.400
[Guest 2]: 18,971 words.

01:14:28.400 --> 01:14:35.200
[Guest 2]: So a good book these days has around 90,000 words or less than that, in fact.

01:14:35.200 --> 01:14:38.160
[Amit Varma]: No, I'll give listeners a better context.

01:14:38.160 --> 01:14:41.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of my guests once transcribed a two hour episode I did with him, and it

01:14:41.720 --> 01:14:43.560
[Amit Varma]: came to 25,000 words.

01:14:43.560 --> 01:14:45.320
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, 18,000 words.

01:14:45.320 --> 01:14:48.720
[Guest 2]: No, but that depends on how fast you're speaking.

01:14:48.720 --> 01:14:49.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:14:49.720 --> 01:14:54.920
[Guest 2]: So this, she spoke for almost two hours, 45 minutes, which is a record.

01:14:54.920 --> 01:14:56.760
[Amit Varma]: And she gave up in the end, she couldn't complete.

01:14:56.760 --> 01:15:00.280
[Amit Varma]: I thought the great master plan is she'll go on till the end of the news cycle and you're

01:15:00.280 --> 01:15:01.280
[Amit Varma]: in the next news cycle.

01:15:01.280 --> 01:15:02.960
[Amit Varma]: And then people have forgotten about the budget.

01:15:02.960 --> 01:15:03.960
[Amit Varma]: But that hasn't happened.

01:15:03.960 --> 01:15:05.360
[Amit Varma]: We don't let these things go.

01:15:05.360 --> 01:15:11.520
[Guest 2]: I managed to listen to it because what happened was at around 1015 in the morning, I was feeling

01:15:11.520 --> 01:15:12.520
[Guest 2]: terribly sleepy.

01:15:12.520 --> 01:15:13.520
[Guest 2]: So I slept.

01:15:13.520 --> 01:15:20.760
[Guest 2]: And then I woke up at around 1145, I woke up and I thought it will be done in an hour.

01:15:20.760 --> 01:15:24.560
[Guest 2]: And then it finished at around 145.

01:15:24.560 --> 01:15:30.320
[Guest 2]: So it was quite otherwise I would have fallen asleep if I hadn't slept before the budget

01:15:30.320 --> 01:15:31.320
[Guest 2]: speech started.

01:15:31.320 --> 01:15:34.960
[Guest 2]: I would have fallen asleep during the course of it just went on and on and on.

01:15:34.960 --> 01:15:42.280
[Guest 2]: And there was, I mean, it was all sorts of things from Kalidasa to, I don't know, I mean,

01:15:42.280 --> 01:15:47.000
[Guest 2]: to the great Harappan civilization, I mean, and a lot of very random posturing also let

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:51.640
[Amit Varma]: us show off our erudition and our knowledge and let us, you know, while we have the two

01:15:51.640 --> 01:15:56.640
[Amit Varma]: Abdullahs in jail, let us quote from a Kashmiri poem written by a Kashmiri poet for senior

01:15:56.640 --> 01:15:58.280
[Amit Varma]: Abdullah, Sheikh Abdullah.

01:15:58.280 --> 01:16:04.040
[Amit Varma]: The irony of all of these things escape these people, but sort of let's kind of talk about

01:16:04.040 --> 01:16:08.440
[Amit Varma]: and the reason I also want to talk about specifics, while this has been a really good discussion

01:16:08.440 --> 01:16:13.640
[Amit Varma]: on the sort of meta level that I like rather indulgently, there has been great public demand

01:16:13.640 --> 01:16:18.240
[Amit Varma]: for Mr. Vivek Kaul to comment on all the nitty gritties of the budgets and a number of people

01:16:18.240 --> 01:16:21.600
[Amit Varma]: even asked me, why, when are you doing an episode on this budget?

01:16:21.600 --> 01:16:26.080
[Amit Varma]: So I didn't plan to do an economics episode so soon.

01:16:26.080 --> 01:16:30.440
[Amit Varma]: But since there was so much public demand here it is, but the next 12 episodes will

01:16:30.440 --> 01:16:33.200
[Amit Varma]: not involve economics, LIC.

01:16:33.200 --> 01:16:38.520
[Amit Varma]: So what you have written about LIC is that at one level is good news, because it means

01:16:38.520 --> 01:16:43.320
[Amit Varma]: that you know, it will become more transparent, hopefully, hopefully, it showed the incentives

01:16:43.320 --> 01:16:44.520
[Amit Varma]: go that way.

01:16:44.520 --> 01:16:49.600
[Amit Varma]: But what you are confused about is that to quote you quote, LIC has acted as the internal

01:16:49.600 --> 01:16:54.920
[Amit Varma]: financier of the government and has been used to bail out the government on multiple occasions.

01:16:54.920 --> 01:16:58.560
[Amit Varma]: So it will be interesting to see whether this equation changes in the future, stop quote.

01:16:58.560 --> 01:17:03.800
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I mean, so there are I mean, obviously, you know, once you list on the stock exchange,

01:17:03.800 --> 01:17:07.360
[Guest 2]: you have to put out a certain amount of information.

01:17:07.360 --> 01:17:10.440
[Guest 2]: So to that limited extent, it's it's a great move.

01:17:10.440 --> 01:17:14.360
[Guest 2]: But then there are a lot of other issues, which will need clarification over a period

01:17:14.360 --> 01:17:15.360
[Guest 2]: of time.

01:17:15.360 --> 01:17:21.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, so LIC as of now, the structure of the LIC is I mean, and you would probably

01:17:21.320 --> 01:17:27.560
[Guest 2]: know better is that it's essentially a pool of investors coming together, and their money

01:17:27.560 --> 01:17:32.040
[Guest 2]: being invested, and then the returns being shared with them, right.

01:17:32.040 --> 01:17:37.040
[Guest 2]: Also, whatever remains goes as dividend to the government.

01:17:37.040 --> 01:17:42.520
[Guest 2]: So you you have to, you know, that that structure has to change, because once you become a listed

01:17:42.520 --> 01:17:49.000
[Guest 2]: entity, there has to be a proper, you know, balance sheet, profit and loss account statement,

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:50.640
[Guest 2]: and so on and so forth.

01:17:50.640 --> 01:17:57.000
[Guest 2]: Then there is this huge thing, as I said about how LIC has rescued so many government IPOs

01:17:57.000 --> 01:18:04.400
[Guest 2]: over and over again, a lot of LIC, you know, the the policy, the endowment and the money

01:18:04.400 --> 01:18:08.480
[Guest 2]: back policies, the money they collect, get simply get invested in government bonds.

01:18:08.480 --> 01:18:13.080
[Guest 2]: So to that extent, it is a very large financier of of the government.

01:18:13.080 --> 01:18:15.480
[Guest 2]: Also, there is the issue of solvency.

01:18:15.480 --> 01:18:21.760
[Guest 2]: I mean, I think the capital backing LIC is some 5 crore rupees or something like that.

01:18:21.760 --> 01:18:26.280
[Guest 2]: And that is primarily because the Indian government, obviously, backs it.

01:18:26.280 --> 01:18:30.160
[Guest 2]: So will the government continue to back it after it is listed?

01:18:30.160 --> 01:18:34.840
[Guest 2]: So there are a lot of questions which it will not be easy to list LIC.

01:18:34.840 --> 01:18:39.040
[Guest 2]: I mean, I guess it'll it'll take at least, I mean, it should take them a minimum of seven,

01:18:39.040 --> 01:18:42.640
[Guest 2]: eight months to just get the process going.

01:18:42.640 --> 01:18:47.440
[Guest 2]: Another thing about this budget, which causes contradiction here is and so now, since we

01:18:47.440 --> 01:18:53.040
[Guest 2]: are moving to a tax system where there will be no exemptions, and so people will not be

01:18:53.040 --> 01:18:57.840
[Guest 2]: encouraged to save because they are saving tax.

01:18:57.840 --> 01:19:00.240
[Guest 2]: And at the other end, you're trying to list LIC.

01:19:00.240 --> 01:19:01.800
[Guest 2]: So LIC is premium.

01:19:01.800 --> 01:19:06.880
[Guest 2]: The main reason that LIC survives is because people want to save tax.

01:19:06.880 --> 01:19:10.960
[Guest 2]: Nobody buys life insurance from LIC, right?

01:19:10.960 --> 01:19:15.560
[Guest 2]: People think they are buying life insurance, what they're buying is essentially a investment

01:19:15.560 --> 01:19:21.120
[Guest 2]: product masquerading as a life insurance product, and something which helps them save.

01:19:21.120 --> 01:19:26.120
[Amit Varma]: They're almost being nudged slash coerced towards it by bad incentives forced upon you

01:19:26.120 --> 01:19:27.120
[Guest 2]: by the government.

01:19:27.120 --> 01:19:31.360
[Guest 2]: Now, see, the other thing that comes out is like, you know, if you look at the these endowment

01:19:31.360 --> 01:19:38.000
[Guest 2]: and the money back policies of LIC, the returns of them are hopelessly low 4%, 5%.

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:42.120
[Guest 2]: It's just that the average Indian or even the average human being cannot sit and calculate

01:19:42.120 --> 01:19:46.680
[Guest 2]: the IRR on the policy that the internal rate of return on the policy that he or she is

01:19:46.680 --> 01:19:47.680
[Guest 2]: buying.

01:19:47.680 --> 01:19:51.760
[Guest 2]: So all this will gradually start to change.

01:19:51.760 --> 01:19:58.720
[Guest 2]: And the moment you take away the tax thing, the tax incentive of investing in insurance,

01:19:58.720 --> 01:20:01.320
[Guest 1]: the business model of LIC goes for a toss.

01:20:01.320 --> 01:20:09.760
[Guest 1]: I think that it is an extremely positive move to think of putting LIC into an IPO and bringing

01:20:09.760 --> 01:20:11.960
[Amit Varma]: it into the markets.

01:20:11.960 --> 01:20:14.760
[Guest 1]: Accountability incentives, everything gets really happy that this has happened.

01:20:14.760 --> 01:20:16.480
[Guest 1]: It's a tough, difficult thing.

01:20:16.480 --> 01:20:19.680
[Guest 1]: You can just see all kinds of people getting unhappy, but this is the right thing to do.

01:20:19.680 --> 01:20:22.600
[Guest 1]: So I'm very happy that that move has taken place.

01:20:22.600 --> 01:20:24.880
[Guest 1]: As Vivek says, there are many hoops to jump.

01:20:24.880 --> 01:20:28.680
[Guest 1]: I want to just emphasize two of those hoops.

01:20:28.680 --> 01:20:36.800
[Guest 1]: The first of them is that we will need regulatory capacity at IRDA and we need to confront basics

01:20:36.800 --> 01:20:43.880
[Guest 1]: about capital adequacy that it's almost amusing how little equity capital there is in LIC.

01:20:43.880 --> 01:20:50.200
[Guest 1]: And LIC has given loans to a lot of the same firms who have defaulted on banks.

01:20:50.200 --> 01:20:54.040
[Guest 1]: And I don't know how that mark-to-market is done inside LIC.

01:20:54.040 --> 01:20:55.040
[Guest 2]: Yeah, exactly.

01:20:55.040 --> 01:20:56.040
[Guest 2]: This is another point.

01:20:56.040 --> 01:20:57.040
[Guest 2]: The bad loans.

01:20:57.040 --> 01:21:00.520
[Guest 2]: So it's like, you know, banks are facing bad loans and LIC has also got to...

01:21:00.520 --> 01:21:02.720
[Guest 1]: LIC has lent to all the same people.

01:21:02.720 --> 01:21:07.520
[Guest 1]: So if there is a problem inside many banks, it's probably a difficult problem inside LIC

01:21:07.520 --> 01:21:08.520
[Guest 1]: as well.

01:21:08.520 --> 01:21:13.740
[Guest 1]: On this note, I also want to emphasize the importance of IFRS accounting.

01:21:13.740 --> 01:21:18.720
[Guest 1]: This is like high-geeky accounting terrain, but I'm one of the people that gets really

01:21:18.720 --> 01:21:24.640
[Guest 1]: happy when you move accounting from a cash-based system to an accrual-based system.

01:21:24.640 --> 01:21:26.640
[Unknown]: And that is what is called NDS.

01:21:26.640 --> 01:21:28.760
[Guest 1]: LIC was on a cash-based system?

01:21:28.760 --> 01:21:35.960
[Guest 1]: There are only two industries in India which are not in NDS at the fervent request of the

01:21:35.960 --> 01:21:36.960
[Guest 1]: regulators.

01:21:36.960 --> 01:21:42.480
[Guest 1]: RBI requested that we continue to do bad accounting for banks and IRDA requested that we continue

01:21:42.480 --> 01:21:45.200
[Guest 1]: to do bad accounting for insurance companies.

01:21:45.200 --> 01:21:49.960
[Guest 1]: So that's one more barrier that I think will end up needing to be crossed, that you really

01:21:49.960 --> 01:21:53.360
[Guest 1]: need accrual-based accounting for an insurance company.

01:21:53.360 --> 01:21:57.720
[Guest 1]: It's just totally wrong to think about an insurance company on a cash basis.

01:21:57.720 --> 01:22:02.000
[Guest 1]: Because the demographic composition of the payouts and the new customers is profoundly

01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:03.000
[Guest 1]: different.

01:22:03.000 --> 01:22:07.960
[Guest 1]: On a cash basis, you may always feel you've got to do accrual-based accounting to think

01:22:07.960 --> 01:22:10.240
[Guest 1]: in a forward-looking way about what's going on.

01:22:10.240 --> 01:22:12.840
[Guest 1]: So I feel that these are hoops to cross.

01:22:12.840 --> 01:22:18.800
[Guest 1]: But the point is, it is this decision that will force a reckoning on these questions,

01:22:18.800 --> 01:22:19.800
[Guest 1]: which is so great.

01:22:19.800 --> 01:22:22.960
[Amit Varma]: So, my next question is about something else.

01:22:22.960 --> 01:22:28.600
[Guest 2]: This also brings us back to what Ajay was saying that, you know, different parts of

01:22:28.600 --> 01:22:30.800
[Guest 2]: the budget have been written by different people.

01:22:30.800 --> 01:22:35.480
[Amit Varma]: No, and I was again going to, my next question was also going to deal with debt dissonance

01:22:35.480 --> 01:22:41.680
[Amit Varma]: and in the process managed to ask a larger question as well, a microcosm and a macrocosm.

01:22:41.680 --> 01:22:46.440
[Amit Varma]: Microcosm of course is that the, interestingly, the NREGA budget has gone down a little bit,

01:22:46.440 --> 01:22:47.440
[Amit Varma]: I think from 70,000.

01:22:47.440 --> 01:22:48.440
[Guest 2]: 71 to 61.

01:22:48.440 --> 01:22:50.240
[Amit Varma]: 71 to 61.

01:22:50.240 --> 01:22:55.120
[Amit Varma]: But the larger question is that this is a government which, and so Mihir Sharma had

01:22:55.120 --> 01:22:59.880
[Amit Varma]: a very interesting tweet about how this government seems to mistake reforms or is trying to recast

01:22:59.880 --> 01:23:03.960
[Amit Varma]: reforms as welfarism, which, you know, is an extremely valid point.

01:23:03.960 --> 01:23:08.760
[Amit Varma]: While it's interesting on the one hand, because all of these guys who are in power now used

01:23:08.760 --> 01:23:13.040
[Amit Varma]: to rail against the welfarism of the Congress, the NREGA and so on, that the Congress did

01:23:13.040 --> 01:23:15.800
[Amit Varma]: circa the late years of the last decade.

01:23:15.800 --> 01:23:19.080
[Amit Varma]: What they have done since is that they have renamed some of those schemes, but they've

01:23:19.080 --> 01:23:20.840
[Amit Varma]: kept a lot of the welfarism going.

01:23:20.840 --> 01:23:24.880
[Amit Varma]: A lot of that welfarism is actually why they won votes in the heartland.

01:23:24.880 --> 01:23:30.960
[Amit Varma]: It's not all, you know, as some allege, it's not all bigotry in Hindu Rashtra, the welfarism

01:23:30.960 --> 01:23:31.960
[Amit Varma]: did help.

01:23:31.960 --> 01:23:35.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, Parthaman did a bunch of pieces on this where he showed that people's perceptions

01:23:35.880 --> 01:23:39.880
[Amit Varma]: of the Modi government was that they're actually doing a lot for the people and many of these

01:23:39.880 --> 01:23:44.280
[Amit Varma]: schemes are delivering, if not for them, they've seen it deliver for others and so on.

01:23:44.280 --> 01:23:49.400
[Amit Varma]: And in an episode I did with Ram Guha for this year's Republic Day, he also pointed

01:23:49.400 --> 01:23:55.080
[Amit Varma]: out and he agreed with me that a lot of Prime Minister Modi's view of the world comes from

01:23:55.080 --> 01:23:58.620
[Amit Varma]: what he has experienced as opposed to what he has read.

01:23:58.620 --> 01:24:03.320
[Amit Varma]: So while a lot of the more abstract concepts which you need to know to run an economy might

01:24:03.320 --> 01:24:07.840
[Amit Varma]: escape him like spontaneous order and positive sumness and so on, he gets the importance

01:24:07.840 --> 01:24:13.760
[Amit Varma]: of things like water and roads and electricity, which, you know, and the delivery of those.

01:24:13.760 --> 01:24:18.440
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, he is someone who actually genuinely does believe in welfarism, ideologically

01:24:18.440 --> 01:24:19.760
[Amit Varma]: as well.

01:24:19.760 --> 01:24:24.240
[Amit Varma]: Given all of this, what's going on here that, you know, they do stress more on welfarism

01:24:24.240 --> 01:24:28.800
[Amit Varma]: than fundamental reforms, but at the same time, the NREGA budget has gone down, is there

01:24:28.800 --> 01:24:29.800
[Guest 2]: some broader thinking?

01:24:29.800 --> 01:24:30.800
[Guest 2]: I don't know.

01:24:30.800 --> 01:24:34.480
[Guest 2]: So which is what left me confused, because when I looked at the numbers, so the NREGA

01:24:34.480 --> 01:24:40.760
[Guest 2]: budgets are down from around 71,000 crore this year to 61,500 crore next year.

01:24:40.760 --> 01:24:46.000
[Guest 2]: But the PM-Kisan allocation continues to be the same at 75,000 crore, even though this

01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:49.040
[Guest 2]: year they'll end up spending only around 54,000 crore.

01:24:49.040 --> 01:24:53.520
[Guest 2]: So my thinking is, you know, if you're giving the landowners some amount of money, you might

01:24:53.520 --> 01:24:57.640
[Guest 2]: as well, you know, spend a little more money on NREGA.

01:24:57.640 --> 01:25:04.160
[Guest 2]: I mean, I mean, I thought that was quite also, you know, when you keep putting equity into

01:25:04.160 --> 01:25:10.680
[Guest 2]: dud companies like MTNL and BSNL, I mean, it's not fair that, you know, you cut 10,000

01:25:10.680 --> 01:25:11.680
[Guest 2]: crore there.

01:25:11.680 --> 01:25:12.680
[Guest 2]: So, I don't know.

01:25:12.680 --> 01:25:19.160
[Guest 2]: I mean, I don't think there is a broad thinking behind all this, they just randomly, you know,

01:25:19.160 --> 01:25:24.320
[Guest 2]: doing stuff here and there, because, you know, this this sort of contradiction is very difficult

01:25:24.320 --> 01:25:25.320
[Guest 2]: to explain.

01:25:25.320 --> 01:25:26.320
[Guest 2]: So,

01:25:26.320 --> 01:25:30.480
[Guest 1]: Sanjiv Gupta Perhaps the political environment surrounding

01:25:30.480 --> 01:25:35.560
[Guest 1]: welfarism changes when there is economic stress.

01:25:35.560 --> 01:25:41.520
[Guest 1]: Perhaps if the same Mr. Modi had presided over a strong economy, his calls could have

01:25:41.520 --> 01:25:42.520
[Guest 1]: been different.

01:25:42.520 --> 01:25:50.120
[Guest 1]: I wonder how much of this push in favor of welfarism is, in fact, the consequence of

01:25:50.120 --> 01:25:51.120
[Guest 1]: poor economic performance.

01:25:51.120 --> 01:25:54.120
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta So to break that down, are you saying, if

01:25:54.120 --> 01:25:57.520
[Amit Varma]: I interpret it correctly, then what you're basically saying is that, look, welfarism,

01:25:57.520 --> 01:26:02.560
[Amit Varma]: perhaps for the word itself, welfarism, it has a positive ring to it makes for good political

01:26:02.560 --> 01:26:06.520
[Amit Varma]: optics that, hey, you know, you guys are suffering, we're going to help you out, we're going to,

01:26:06.520 --> 01:26:09.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, these are all the handouts we are sort of going to do.

01:26:09.680 --> 01:26:13.280
[Amit Varma]: But of course, you know, economists would know that there is a tradeoff between redistribution

01:26:13.280 --> 01:26:16.660
[Amit Varma]: and growth, and growth is what actually lifts people out of poverty.

01:26:16.660 --> 01:26:21.320
[Amit Varma]: But because growth isn't happening, and all of that, they're going for the political optics,

01:26:21.320 --> 01:26:22.320
[Amit Varma]: is that right?

01:26:22.320 --> 01:26:25.000
[Guest 1]: Sanjiv Gupta Yeah, but I don't know how much of this is

01:26:25.000 --> 01:26:32.640
[Guest 1]: a reflection of the underlying ideology, as opposed to an expedient response to the difficulties

01:26:32.640 --> 01:26:33.640
[Unknown]: that we face.

01:26:33.640 --> 01:26:34.640
[Guest 2]: Sanjiv Gupta Incentives again, therefore,

01:26:34.640 --> 01:26:36.360
[Guest 2]: Sanjiv Gupta In fact, you know, another thing, this sort

01:26:36.360 --> 01:26:42.040
[Guest 2]: of slightly different point, you know, a lot of media this time, went around reporting

01:26:42.040 --> 01:26:43.880
[Guest 2]: that subsidies have been cut.

01:26:43.880 --> 01:26:48.840
[Guest 2]: Now, you know, that that was so wrong at many levels, with subsidies have not been cut,

01:26:48.840 --> 01:26:52.120
[Guest 2]: the government is just not paying the subsidies, okay.

01:26:52.120 --> 01:26:55.600
[Guest 2]: So take take like, I mean, Food Corporation of India, best example,

01:26:55.600 --> 01:26:57.920
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta Which is actually your favorite company.

01:26:57.920 --> 01:27:01.080
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta I was thinking when you said favorite company,

01:27:01.080 --> 01:27:03.560
[Guest 2]: you would say Food Corporation, but that's okay.

01:27:03.560 --> 01:27:08.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, look at Food Corporation of India, right?

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:14.440
[Guest 2]: So the food subsidies for 2019-20, when the budget was presented, were around 1,84,000

01:27:14.440 --> 01:27:15.480
[Guest 2]: crore.

01:27:15.480 --> 01:27:20.080
[Guest 2]: In the revised number, it's around 1,09,000 crore, okay.

01:27:20.080 --> 01:27:25.400
[Guest 2]: So that essentially means that the food subsidy has been cut by close to 75,000 crore.

01:27:25.400 --> 01:27:32.960
[Guest 2]: Food Corporation of India's subsidy bill this year stands at 3,17,905 crore, okay.

01:27:32.960 --> 01:27:38.040
[Guest 2]: So it's a difference of around 2,10,000 crore, which the government has to pay FCI, but it

01:27:38.040 --> 01:27:39.040
[Guest 2]: is not.

01:27:39.040 --> 01:27:43.080
[Guest 2]: Now, the government has to pay FCI because FCI is buying rice and wheat from farmers

01:27:43.080 --> 01:27:46.560
[Guest 2]: directly at a certain minimum support price.

01:27:46.560 --> 01:27:50.120
[Guest 2]: And it's selling that rice and wheat at a very low price through the public distribution

01:27:50.120 --> 01:27:51.120
[Guest 2]: system.

01:27:51.120 --> 01:27:54.560
[Guest 2]: So that difference has to be paid for so that, you know, FCI remains a going.

01:27:54.560 --> 01:27:56.520
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta That's a mechanism of the food subsidy.

01:27:56.520 --> 01:27:59.320
[Guest 2]: Sanjiv Gupta So, so it's not that food subsidies been

01:27:59.320 --> 01:28:02.120
[Guest 2]: cut, you know, food subsidies still the same.

01:28:02.120 --> 01:28:04.440
[Guest 2]: It's just that FCI is not being paid.

01:28:04.440 --> 01:28:09.080
[Guest 2]: And FCI is now being partly financed out of the National Small Savings Fund, which is

01:28:09.080 --> 01:28:14.760
[Guest 2]: where the investment that you know, people make in the National Savings Scheme, NSS goes

01:28:14.760 --> 01:28:15.800
[Guest 2]: to.

01:28:15.800 --> 01:28:18.360
[Guest 2]: So they are essentially borrowing money from that.

01:28:18.360 --> 01:28:21.320
[Guest 2]: And the remaining part of the money is being borrowed from banks.

01:28:21.320 --> 01:28:24.080
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta So is NSS forced to lend to the FCI?

01:28:24.080 --> 01:28:27.600
[Guest 2]: Sanjiv Gupta It's like it's government one hand, money

01:28:27.600 --> 01:28:28.600
[Amit Varma]: moving from one hand.

01:28:28.600 --> 01:28:31.320
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta Are we incentivized to invest in the NSS because

01:28:31.320 --> 01:28:32.320
[Guest 1]: of tax savings?

01:28:32.320 --> 01:28:33.320
[Guest 1]: Sanjiv Gupta The rates are very high.

01:28:33.320 --> 01:28:36.760
[Amit Varma]: Sanjiv Gupta So basically, these sort of coercive regulations

01:28:36.760 --> 01:28:42.920
[Amit Varma]: force us to invest in NSS to save tax, and that money then goes to pay FCI bills, which

01:28:42.920 --> 01:28:46.720
[Guest 2]: the government isn't paying, and then it is claiming that hey, we will do subsidies.

01:28:46.720 --> 01:28:49.200
[Guest 2]: Sanjiv Gupta So there are multiple problems here.

01:28:49.200 --> 01:28:55.600
[Guest 2]: So the first thing is that, so FCI is buying this rice and wheat, and it ends up buying

01:28:55.600 --> 01:28:57.120
[Guest 2]: an excess amount of rice and wheat.

01:28:57.120 --> 01:29:04.680
[Guest 2]: So I was just seeing looking at the numbers for as of January, FCI had around 75 lakh

01:29:04.680 --> 01:29:10.840
[Guest 2]: tons of rice and wheat when it needed to have some half of that or something like that,

01:29:10.840 --> 01:29:11.840
[Guest 2]: right.

01:29:11.840 --> 01:29:18.360
[Guest 2]: The excess stock has been paid for by the FCI, which has borrowed money from NSS, and

01:29:18.360 --> 01:29:19.440
[Guest 2]: from banks.

01:29:19.440 --> 01:29:25.200
[Guest 2]: So basically, it's been paid for by UNI, right, I mean, it's ultimately comes down to us.

01:29:25.200 --> 01:29:29.440
[Guest 2]: The second thing that happens here, and this is where it all starts getting very, very

01:29:29.440 --> 01:29:35.160
[Guest 2]: bizarre is that when the FCI borrows all this money from banks, obviously, there is going

01:29:35.160 --> 01:29:41.200
[Guest 2]: to be crowding out, less money left for others to borrow, and your interest rates remain

01:29:41.200 --> 01:29:42.780
[Guest 2]: where and you know.

01:29:42.780 --> 01:29:49.920
[Guest 2]: The other interesting thing is because NSS needs money, the interest rates on that continue

01:29:49.920 --> 01:29:55.240
[Guest 2]: to remain higher than fixed deposits, because NSS needs money, because it has to finance

01:29:55.240 --> 01:29:59.400
[Guest 2]: FCI, it has to finance the National Highway Authorities of India.

01:29:59.400 --> 01:30:05.700
[Guest 2]: So all this comes together to essentially ensure that monetary policy does not work,

01:30:05.700 --> 01:30:12.600
[Guest 2]: because the government needs a high interest rate environment to keep all this going.

01:30:12.600 --> 01:30:16.800
[Guest 2]: And because it needs a high interest rate environment, your, you know, your interest

01:30:16.800 --> 01:30:21.600
[Guest 2]: on small savings schemes continue to remain higher than interest on FDs.

01:30:21.600 --> 01:30:26.240
[Guest 2]: So because interest on small savings schemes continue to remain high, FD interest rates

01:30:26.240 --> 01:30:32.040
[Guest 2]: cannot be slashed, even though, you know, the monetary policy has been cutting the repo

01:30:32.040 --> 01:30:33.600
[Amit Varma]: rate for a while now.

01:30:33.600 --> 01:30:37.760
[Amit Varma]: And you've written articles about how cutting the repo rate doesn't actually make a practical

01:30:37.760 --> 01:30:38.760
[Guest 2]: difference in our lives.

01:30:38.760 --> 01:30:39.760
[Guest 2]: As of now, it doesn't.

01:30:39.760 --> 01:30:40.760
[Guest 1]: It's been sort of...

01:30:40.760 --> 01:30:45.240
[Guest 1]: I just want to riff on what he has been describing.

01:30:45.240 --> 01:30:47.080
[Guest 1]: Everything you say is, of course, correct.

01:30:47.080 --> 01:30:50.120
[Guest 1]: But here's the deeper story of what happens.

01:30:50.120 --> 01:30:53.960
[Guest 1]: The first element is that social systems are complicated.

01:30:53.960 --> 01:30:58.660
[Guest 1]: And each move you make has unintended consequences.

01:30:58.660 --> 01:31:05.880
[Guest 1]: And the second problem is, this is the consequence of low strategy, high tactics.

01:31:05.880 --> 01:31:11.760
[Guest 1]: So every day, one feels very clever, coming out with one more element of a solution, which

01:31:11.760 --> 01:31:14.300
[Guest 1]: seems to solve my point of pain today.

01:31:14.300 --> 01:31:19.480
[Guest 1]: But actually, that just creates a more and more intricate web of interlocking policy

01:31:19.480 --> 01:31:23.320
[Guest 1]: constraints that tie down policymakers in knots.

01:31:23.320 --> 01:31:26.800
[Guest 1]: And this is why there is a greater role for strategy.

01:31:26.800 --> 01:31:34.160
[Guest 1]: So very often, people tend to wonder that what's wrong with just taking one day at a

01:31:34.160 --> 01:31:35.160
[Guest 1]: time?

01:31:35.160 --> 01:31:36.160
[Guest 1]: You see a problem, you solve the problem.

01:31:36.160 --> 01:31:38.200
[Guest 1]: You see a problem, you solve the problem.

01:31:38.200 --> 01:31:39.400
[Guest 1]: It doesn't suffice.

01:31:39.400 --> 01:31:42.720
[Guest 1]: In public policy, it's important to have a strategic sense.

01:31:42.720 --> 01:31:43.880
[Guest 1]: Who am I?

01:31:43.880 --> 01:31:45.280
[Guest 1]: What is the role of the state?

01:31:45.280 --> 01:31:47.520
[Guest 1]: What market failure am I addressing?

01:31:47.520 --> 01:31:54.920
[Guest 1]: What is the detritus of inherited, messy interventions and institutions that we need to wind down

01:31:54.920 --> 01:31:56.480
[Guest 1]: gradually?

01:31:56.480 --> 01:32:01.280
[Guest 1]: And then many decisions can be taken that will put us on a better path.

01:32:01.280 --> 01:32:04.880
[Guest 2]: Ajay Shah So I just wanted to sort of make one more

01:32:04.880 --> 01:32:05.880
[Guest 2]: point.

01:32:05.880 --> 01:32:06.880
[Guest 2]: No, no, that's fine.

01:32:06.880 --> 01:32:09.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's a very important point.

01:32:09.640 --> 01:32:15.160
[Guest 2]: So no, what I wanted to say was, Ajay was talking about how the rate of investment has

01:32:15.160 --> 01:32:16.160
[Guest 2]: come down dramatically.

01:32:16.160 --> 01:32:17.160
[Guest 2]: Okay.

01:32:17.160 --> 01:32:19.200
[Guest 2]: So I'm obviously simplifying things here a little.

01:32:19.200 --> 01:32:24.520
[Guest 2]: So when, because the rate of investment has come down, obviously jobs haven't been created

01:32:24.520 --> 01:32:26.840
[Guest 2]: at the same pace as when needed.

01:32:26.840 --> 01:32:32.400
[Guest 2]: When jobs haven't been created, obviously a lot of people are not making money or they're

01:32:32.400 --> 01:32:35.180
[Guest 2]: not making the kind of money they would have otherwise made.

01:32:35.180 --> 01:32:37.720
[Guest 2]: So income growth has also come down.

01:32:37.720 --> 01:32:42.480
[Guest 2]: Because income growth has come down, people have been consuming a larger proportion of

01:32:42.480 --> 01:32:47.000
[Guest 2]: their incomes or they have been borrowing to finance consumption.

01:32:47.000 --> 01:32:53.800
[Guest 2]: So when you do both, obviously what happens, your rate of savings comes down, right?

01:32:53.800 --> 01:32:58.000
[Guest 2]: In all this environment, while the rate of savings has been coming down, the public sector

01:32:58.000 --> 01:33:03.520
[Guest 2]: borrowing, which is central government, state governments, our budget has been going up,

01:33:03.520 --> 01:33:04.520
[Guest 2]: right?

01:33:04.520 --> 01:33:06.840
[Guest 2]: So how will interest rates come down?

01:33:06.840 --> 01:33:09.680
[Guest 2]: So it's all, it's not like you're doing this and that doesn't get impacted.

01:33:09.680 --> 01:33:13.080
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's all connected at some level.

01:33:13.080 --> 01:33:16.880
[Guest 2]: And a lot of it is, you know, people don't even understand that it is connected.

01:33:16.880 --> 01:33:17.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:33:17.880 --> 01:33:22.360
[Amit Varma]: And so my next question is, again, something you've written about with a certain amount

01:33:22.360 --> 01:33:26.440
[Amit Varma]: of bemusement and which the middle class was very, you know, eagerly looking at, which

01:33:26.440 --> 01:33:28.560
[Amit Varma]: is what is going to happen with income tax.

01:33:28.560 --> 01:33:32.160
[Amit Varma]: And there was this initial impression that, oh, yes, the taxes have gone down.

01:33:32.160 --> 01:33:33.600
[Amit Varma]: But that is not the case.

01:33:33.600 --> 01:33:38.280
[Amit Varma]: And most people are still confused about whether they will be paying more or less.

01:33:38.280 --> 01:33:42.760
[Guest 2]: So basically, you know, the government wants you to understand the Income Tax Act.

01:33:42.760 --> 01:33:49.280
[Guest 2]: And it also wants you to know how to use an Excel sheet and figure out as to which is

01:33:49.280 --> 01:33:50.280
[Guest 2]: the better system for you.

01:33:50.280 --> 01:33:56.600
[Guest 2]: But largely, you know, if you are the kind who uses the deductions and exemptions that

01:33:56.600 --> 01:34:02.000
[Guest 2]: are available, you are better off on the present system.

01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:05.460
[Guest 2]: And from what I've been told, I mean, I haven't read the finance bill.

01:34:05.460 --> 01:34:09.680
[Guest 2]: From what I've been told, if you move to the new system, you cannot go back to the old

01:34:09.680 --> 01:34:10.680
[Guest 2]: one.

01:34:10.680 --> 01:34:16.360
[Guest 2]: Now, I mean, so I think, you know, if the idea was to simplify, there was no point in

01:34:16.360 --> 01:34:17.360
[Guest 2]: having two systems.

01:34:17.360 --> 01:34:24.480
[Guest 2]: I mean, you could have had even lower rates, so as to ensure that the actual tax comes

01:34:24.480 --> 01:34:25.480
[Guest 2]: down.

01:34:25.480 --> 01:34:26.480
[Guest 2]: Okay.

01:34:26.480 --> 01:34:27.480
[Guest 2]: And incomes go up.

01:34:27.480 --> 01:34:28.480
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:34:28.480 --> 01:34:33.000
[Guest 2]: But I think as of now, and this obviously is a short term solution, people, there has

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:36.920
[Guest 2]: to be more money in the hands of people, you know, this is not the time to tax.

01:34:36.920 --> 01:34:42.840
[Guest 2]: Now, the problem here is, one is that, you know, whether there is more money or not in

01:34:42.840 --> 01:34:46.600
[Guest 2]: the hands of people, that in itself is a question.

01:34:46.600 --> 01:34:51.600
[Guest 2]: And a lot of it is psychological, you know, when, as a nation, we are obsessed with the

01:34:51.600 --> 01:34:52.600
[Guest 2]: government budget.

01:34:52.600 --> 01:34:54.280
[Guest 2]: Now, why is that?

01:34:54.280 --> 01:35:00.400
[Guest 2]: That is because finance ministers have a proclivity of changing, you know, income tax rates or

01:35:00.400 --> 01:35:04.160
[Guest 2]: introducing new exemptions, new deductions, so on and so forth.

01:35:04.160 --> 01:35:11.640
[Guest 2]: So, our obsession with the budget is not because we want to know, whether we have become protectionist

01:35:11.640 --> 01:35:12.640
[Guest 2]: or not.

01:35:12.640 --> 01:35:18.280
[Guest 2]: It is because all of us want to know whether our take home is growing, or we'll have to

01:35:18.280 --> 01:35:19.280
[Guest 2]: pay more tax.

01:35:19.280 --> 01:35:22.040
[Guest 2]: So, at the end of the day, it's very, very psychological.

01:35:22.040 --> 01:35:28.080
[Guest 2]: Now, if you had actually cut taxes, and if you had clearly told people that, yes, the

01:35:28.080 --> 01:35:35.480
[Guest 2]: money in your hands is going to go up, they were more likely to spend or, you know, essentially

01:35:35.480 --> 01:35:36.680
[Guest 2]: consume more.

01:35:36.680 --> 01:35:40.480
[Guest 2]: And that would have sort of helped the economy in a very small sort of way.

01:35:40.480 --> 01:35:44.480
[Guest 2]: But here, what we ended up doing was creating this confusion.

01:35:44.480 --> 01:35:47.280
[Guest 2]: And you have now all the CAs badgering their heads.

01:35:47.280 --> 01:35:51.800
[Guest 2]: And I think this government just wants to make sure that CAs make more and more money.

01:35:51.800 --> 01:35:55.760
[Amit Varma]: You regret not being a CA, Vivek?

01:35:55.760 --> 01:35:56.760
[Guest 2]: You regret not being a CA?

01:35:56.760 --> 01:36:01.400
[Guest 2]: I mean, I regret a lot of things in life, but that can be an episode in itself.

01:36:01.400 --> 01:36:07.400
[Guest 2]: No, so I found it very, very, this was a low lying, low hanging fruit, which could have

01:36:07.400 --> 01:36:08.400
[Guest 2]: been.

01:36:08.400 --> 01:36:12.360
[Guest 2]: Also, the interesting thing is that in the budget speech, the finance minister said that

01:36:12.360 --> 01:36:16.320
[Guest 2]: the government will lose 40,000 crore because of this new system.

01:36:16.320 --> 01:36:21.720
[Guest 2]: But if you check the receipts of the government, the assumption is personal income tax collections

01:36:21.720 --> 01:36:22.720
[Guest 2]: will go up 14%.

01:36:22.720 --> 01:36:29.320
[Guest 2]: So, how is that possible that 40,000 crores will be lost and there is an increase of 14%

01:36:29.320 --> 01:36:30.320
[Guest 2]: there?

01:36:30.320 --> 01:36:32.280
[Guest 2]: I mean, this is a little bizarre.

01:36:32.280 --> 01:36:37.160
[Guest 2]: In an environment where they have assumed that the nominal GDP growth will be 10%, if

01:36:37.160 --> 01:36:43.920
[Guest 2]: you look at the gross tax numbers for this year, the increase assumed is 4%, whereas

01:36:43.920 --> 01:36:48.920
[Guest 2]: if you look at the gross tax numbers for the first nine months, they are 3% lower than

01:36:48.920 --> 01:36:50.320
[Guest 2]: the last year's thing.

01:36:50.320 --> 01:36:54.920
[Guest 2]: So, in this environment, how can you assume a 14% growth?

01:36:54.920 --> 01:37:00.200
[Guest 2]: So, there are a lot of, in fact, the budget math is very, very shaky this time around.

01:37:00.200 --> 01:37:04.480
[Amit Varma]: Not only is the math shaky, the shaky math is based on dubious data.

01:37:04.480 --> 01:37:07.920
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, is it fair to say that to some extent, these guys are winging it too?

01:37:07.920 --> 01:37:08.920
[Guest 2]: Oh, yes.

01:37:08.920 --> 01:37:14.520
[Guest 2]: In fact, yesterday, late night, I saw this beautiful video where two old men, A.K. Bhattacharya,

01:37:14.520 --> 01:37:18.240
[Amit Varma]: who's the editorial director of Binistandar and T.N. Nainan, who's the chairman, and they

01:37:18.240 --> 01:37:24.280
[Guest 2]: were talking, and it's an 18 minute video, which everyone should watch.

01:37:24.280 --> 01:37:29.280
[Guest 2]: And Nainan kept making this point over and over again as to, you know, should we take

01:37:29.280 --> 01:37:30.280
[Guest 2]: these numbers seriously?

01:37:30.280 --> 01:37:34.520
[Guest 2]: So, and, you know, nobody has seen more budgets in India than Nainan has.

01:37:34.520 --> 01:37:36.120
[Amit Varma]: He's that old?

01:37:36.120 --> 01:37:37.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:37:37.120 --> 01:37:38.120
[Amit Varma]: No, no.

01:37:38.120 --> 01:37:42.560
[Guest 2]: I mean, there are people who've seen more budgets, but no one has analysed more budgets.

01:37:42.560 --> 01:37:46.240
[Guest 1]: I want to look at this in a larger problem of the republic.

01:37:46.240 --> 01:37:49.280
[Guest 1]: Okay, so let's take one step back and say, why do we have a budget?

01:37:49.280 --> 01:37:57.480
[Guest 1]: Okay, we have a budget because the legislature wants to have oversight on the executive.

01:37:57.480 --> 01:38:01.960
[Guest 1]: The legislature wants to say to the executive, show me what taxes you will collect.

01:38:01.960 --> 01:38:03.960
[Guest 1]: Show me how you will spend it.

01:38:03.960 --> 01:38:10.160
[Guest 1]: I must be satisfied that your spending plans are consistent with my political values and

01:38:10.160 --> 01:38:11.160
[Guest 1]: beliefs.

01:38:11.160 --> 01:38:13.520
[Guest 1]: Okay, so that's the concept of the budget.

01:38:13.520 --> 01:38:14.520
[Guest 1]: Or take a corporation.

01:38:14.520 --> 01:38:15.520
[Guest 1]: Okay.

01:38:15.520 --> 01:38:16.520
[Guest 1]: Why do we have a budget?

01:38:16.520 --> 01:38:19.840
[Guest 1]: Because the board mistrusts the management.

01:38:19.840 --> 01:38:24.400
[Guest 1]: And that is why a budget is established, whereby the management is on a tight leash.

01:38:24.400 --> 01:38:31.160
[Guest 1]: And through the year, the legislature has to hold the executive accountable for what

01:38:31.160 --> 01:38:38.080
[Guest 1]: it has done in terms of the actual operationalisation of the taxation side, and of the spending

01:38:38.080 --> 01:38:39.080
[Guest 1]: side.

01:38:39.080 --> 01:38:45.200
[Guest 1]: Okay, so for example, all of us reading about news in the United States, it is so interesting

01:38:45.200 --> 01:38:56.200
[Guest 1]: and fascinating to discover that when Congress voted for money to be given as aid to Ukraine,

01:38:56.200 --> 01:39:01.280
[Guest 1]: it was illegal for Donald Trump to withhold that money.

01:39:01.280 --> 01:39:05.920
[Guest 1]: Because when the legislature votes on a certain spending, you have to do it.

01:39:05.920 --> 01:39:11.360
[Guest 1]: That is the meaning of being a representative democracy, where political power ultimately

01:39:11.360 --> 01:39:14.560
[Guest 1]: vests with the legislature.

01:39:14.560 --> 01:39:19.440
[Guest 1]: I feel that what we're getting in India today is a part of that larger problem, which is

01:39:19.440 --> 01:39:27.680
[Guest 1]: the collapse of the legislature as an institution, where we go through a show of some tax proposals

01:39:27.680 --> 01:39:33.720
[Guest 1]: and some spending proposals, and the year unfolds in very different ways.

01:39:33.720 --> 01:39:39.560
[Guest 1]: And the legislature frankly exerts no force on the executive to create accountability.

01:39:39.560 --> 01:39:44.520
[Amit Varma]: And the executive comes from the legislature, so you know, which is, you know, not the case

01:39:44.520 --> 01:39:47.000
[Amit Varma]: in the US where you have a separate election for the president.

01:39:47.000 --> 01:39:49.640
[Guest 2]: In fact, I'll just give an example on what Ajay said.

01:39:49.640 --> 01:39:57.120
[Guest 2]: So in 2018-19, the government expected to earn a total GST of 6,26,000 crore.

01:39:57.120 --> 01:39:59.640
[Guest 2]: It was revised to 5,26,000 crore.

01:39:59.640 --> 01:40:04.840
[Guest 2]: Finally, they managed to collect 4,58,000 crore, which is 25% lower.

01:40:04.840 --> 01:40:10.720
[Guest 2]: What is the point of making these projections if they're going to be so widely, you know,

01:40:10.720 --> 01:40:11.720
[Amit Varma]: of the things?

01:40:11.720 --> 01:40:15.600
[Amit Varma]: So does that then merit a deeper look at the electoral system?

01:40:15.600 --> 01:40:22.640
[Amit Varma]: If you're saying that, you know, the legislator and the executive are too much in lockstep,

01:40:22.640 --> 01:40:26.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, unlike the US, for example, where there's a separate election for the president

01:40:26.040 --> 01:40:29.400
[Amit Varma]: and you know, the Congress and the Senate are separate and they can, you know, they

01:40:29.400 --> 01:40:30.880
[Amit Varma]: can act as a check on each other.

01:40:30.880 --> 01:40:31.880
[Amit Varma]: That's not the case here.

01:40:31.880 --> 01:40:36.560
[Amit Varma]: And would it also be fair to say that the legislature has, you know, the anti-defection

01:40:36.560 --> 01:40:37.560
[Amit Varma]: law plays a part.

01:40:37.560 --> 01:40:41.920
[Amit Varma]: One of the unintended consequences is that you cannot speak against your party, for example,

01:40:41.920 --> 01:40:44.600
[Amit Varma]: and therefore you could run parliament from an Excel sheet.

01:40:44.600 --> 01:40:46.560
[Amit Varma]: You don't need people to even show up.

01:40:46.560 --> 01:40:49.320
[Amit Varma]: I've had an episode on this in the past.

01:40:49.320 --> 01:40:57.160
[Guest 1]: I do think that of the three branches of government in India, the legislature has shaped up as

01:40:57.160 --> 01:40:59.200
[Guest 1]: the weakest component.

01:40:59.200 --> 01:41:04.240
[Guest 1]: It is not pulling its weight because of the anti-defection bill.

01:41:04.240 --> 01:41:11.080
[Guest 1]: The legislative negotiation now only takes place between the heads of the political parties,

01:41:11.080 --> 01:41:13.240
[Guest 1]: but not the average parliamentarian.

01:41:13.240 --> 01:41:17.900
[Guest 1]: So parliamentarians have switched off, frankly, they don't care about legislation.

01:41:17.900 --> 01:41:20.880
[Guest 1]: When is the last time there was a private member bill?

01:41:20.880 --> 01:41:23.400
[Guest 1]: So bills are drafted by joint secretaries.

01:41:23.400 --> 01:41:30.640
[Guest 1]: This is really a travesty that the legislative function is now being taken over by the executives.

01:41:30.640 --> 01:41:34.040
[Guest 1]: And I think this is an important failure of Indian democracy.

01:41:34.040 --> 01:41:38.320
[Guest 1]: I do not understand the problem enough to be able to think about how to solve it.

01:41:38.320 --> 01:41:44.360
[Guest 1]: But I think it's important to recognize that the weakest piece of our constitutional system

01:41:44.360 --> 01:41:46.540
[Guest 1]: today is the legislature.

01:41:46.540 --> 01:41:52.840
[Guest 1]: On the same note, you may remember in the Kelkar and Shah book, when we talk about decentralization,

01:41:52.840 --> 01:41:59.840
[Guest 1]: the only important caveat that we have is the unchecked power of a chief minister at

01:41:59.840 --> 01:42:00.840
[Guest 1]: a state level.

01:42:00.840 --> 01:42:05.120
[Guest 1]: We simply don't have enough check and balance surrounding a chief minister and a chief minister

01:42:05.120 --> 01:42:07.800
[Guest 1]: can easily become a bit despotic.

01:42:07.800 --> 01:42:10.120
[Guest 1]: And then that is no foundation for performance.

01:42:10.120 --> 01:42:16.080
[Guest 1]: We need to think more carefully about how these institutions can evolve so that there

01:42:16.080 --> 01:42:21.240
[Guest 1]: is an everyday check and balance between legislature and executive at the state level as well.

01:42:21.240 --> 01:42:26.520
[Amit Varma]: No, very wise words and I mean, an example of a despotic chief minister who then became

01:42:26.520 --> 01:42:31.720
[Amit Varma]: prime minister and tried to be as despotic is coming to mind, but I won't say it here.

01:42:31.720 --> 01:42:37.080
[Amit Varma]: So you know, let's kind of, I'll obviously link all your respective pieces from the show

01:42:37.080 --> 01:42:40.720
[Amit Varma]: notes so people can dive into them for the details.

01:42:40.720 --> 01:42:45.980
[Amit Varma]: Vivek has many entertaining things to say about Nirmala Tai's budget speech.

01:42:45.980 --> 01:42:53.440
[Amit Varma]: So let's kind of wind up now and sort of, I'll ask both of you, you know, are you hopeful

01:42:53.440 --> 01:42:58.080
[Amit Varma]: of the system changing where the budget is this big media tamasha, but it is actually

01:42:58.080 --> 01:43:01.120
[Amit Varma]: just people winging it and it really doesn't mean anything.

01:43:01.120 --> 01:43:06.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, I mean, barring a crisis, you've been an inside of, you know, in policy circles

01:43:06.280 --> 01:43:11.120
[Amit Varma]: for decades, if that doesn't make you feel too old, Ajay, you know, is there also an

01:43:11.120 --> 01:43:15.560
[Amit Varma]: impetus besides the standard impetus of, oh, we may have a crisis or oh, there may be something

01:43:15.560 --> 01:43:17.080
[Amit Varma]: political besides that.

01:43:17.080 --> 01:43:23.680
[Amit Varma]: Is there also an incentive from elite intellectual circle to a recognition of this problem or

01:43:23.680 --> 01:43:27.000
[Amit Varma]: everyone's just sort of improvising with the moment?

01:43:27.000 --> 01:43:34.060
[Guest 1]: I think that inside the BJP also, like everywhere else, there is a perception of difficulties

01:43:34.060 --> 01:43:35.840
[Guest 1]: in the economy.

01:43:35.840 --> 01:43:43.840
[Guest 1]: And I think that every politician in India is sincerely incentivized to understand these

01:43:43.840 --> 01:43:46.160
[Guest 1]: events and to think of what to do different.

01:43:46.160 --> 01:43:49.560
[Guest 1]: So in that sense, I think Indian democracy is working.

01:43:49.560 --> 01:43:54.520
[Guest 1]: No politician wants to go into elections, maybe a state election, with one hand tied

01:43:54.520 --> 01:43:57.840
[Guest 1]: behind their back, owing to poor performance.

01:43:57.840 --> 01:44:05.520
[Guest 1]: So let's not think that elections in India have degenerated to a point where performance

01:44:05.520 --> 01:44:06.560
[Guest 1]: does not count.

01:44:06.560 --> 01:44:07.560
[Guest 1]: Performance always counts.

01:44:07.560 --> 01:44:08.560
[Guest 1]: And

01:44:08.560 --> 01:44:11.520
[Guest 1]: A few state elections have shown that now.

01:44:11.520 --> 01:44:18.720
[Guest 1]: So I think every politician in India sees that we had a 20 year run of high growth from

01:44:18.720 --> 01:44:19.920
[Guest 1]: 91 to 2011.

01:44:19.920 --> 01:44:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And that something has gone wrong.

01:44:21.320 --> 01:44:24.120
[Amit Varma]: But actually, I mean, you can you can cherry pick evidence, but you can also come to the

01:44:24.120 --> 01:44:29.800
[Amit Varma]: opposite conclusion from evidence, for example, 2019, you know, this government did win after

01:44:29.800 --> 01:44:32.480
[Amit Varma]: five years of disastrous economic management.

01:44:32.480 --> 01:44:36.880
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, they had a landslide win in the UP elections after DEMO.

01:44:36.880 --> 01:44:40.280
[Guest 1]: So I'm not here to say that performance is the only thing.

01:44:40.280 --> 01:44:44.720
[Guest 1]: The limited question that I would ask you is that if you could have a one on one private

01:44:44.720 --> 01:44:49.960
[Guest 1]: conversation with anybody in Indian politics, and you would pose this question that as the

01:44:49.960 --> 01:44:55.360
[Guest 1]: incumbent, would you have rather walked into the 2019 election holding good performance?

01:44:55.360 --> 01:44:58.040
[Guest 1]: I think the answer will be loud and clear.

01:44:58.040 --> 01:45:05.120
[Guest 1]: Yes, that the leadership of Modi and Amit Shah pulled off a victory against all odds.

01:45:05.120 --> 01:45:11.360
[Guest 1]: But if they could dream of a different world, they would have loved to go into that election

01:45:11.360 --> 01:45:12.360
[Guest 1]: with better performance.

01:45:12.360 --> 01:45:15.600
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the counterfactual, therefore, is that had they actually delivered on a lot

01:45:15.600 --> 01:45:20.480
[Amit Varma]: of their rhetoric from 2014, they could have won an even more landslide win in 2019.

01:45:20.480 --> 01:45:26.960
[Guest 1]: So I don't think that any politician would like to go back to elections, holding bad

01:45:26.960 --> 01:45:28.200
[Guest 1]: performance.

01:45:28.200 --> 01:45:33.280
[Guest 1]: And I think we are increasingly getting the point all over India, that there was great

01:45:33.280 --> 01:45:36.480
[Guest 1]: GDP growth from 1991 to 2011.

01:45:36.480 --> 01:45:39.600
[Guest 1]: And from 2011 till today, something has gone wrong.

01:45:39.600 --> 01:45:45.880
[Guest 1]: And we are at the early stages of this cogitation of developing the third paradigm of Indian

01:45:45.880 --> 01:45:47.400
[Guest 1]: economic policy.

01:45:47.400 --> 01:45:53.240
[Guest 1]: And I'm optimistic that things will change, that we are a remarkable country.

01:45:53.240 --> 01:46:00.800
[Guest 1]: We are a precocious country, where at a very low level of per capita GDP, at a time when

01:46:00.800 --> 01:46:08.160
[Guest 1]: female literacy was 6%, we enacted a remarkable constitution.

01:46:08.160 --> 01:46:14.640
[Guest 1]: We are a country that is a child of Gandhiji, Tagore and Nehru, and we'll get better.

01:46:14.640 --> 01:46:15.640
[Amit Varma]: Wise words.

01:46:15.640 --> 01:46:19.720
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, so next year, when the budget rolls around, you see yourself writing pretty much

01:46:19.720 --> 01:46:23.960
[Amit Varma]: the same kind of pieces, at which point even Siddhant cannot bemoan it on Twitter, because

01:46:23.960 --> 01:46:25.480
[Amit Varma]: he will be repeating himself.

01:46:25.480 --> 01:46:27.600
[Guest 2]: Difficult thing to say.

01:46:27.600 --> 01:46:32.040
[Guest 2]: But yeah, I mean, on past evidence, one would say the same.

01:46:32.040 --> 01:46:34.040
[Guest 2]: Bad news will sort of continue.

01:46:34.040 --> 01:46:37.160
[Guest 2]: No, I mean, see, the thing is this.

01:46:37.160 --> 01:46:42.240
[Guest 2]: So until, you know, a few days back, the nominal GDP growth for this year was supposed to be

01:46:42.240 --> 01:46:45.040
[Guest 2]: at a 43-year low.

01:46:45.040 --> 01:46:49.880
[Guest 2]: But then since we revised last year's data, so this year's data is suddenly now looking

01:46:49.880 --> 01:46:50.880
[Guest 2]: a little better.

01:46:50.880 --> 01:46:53.400
[Guest 2]: So, now we are at a 17-year low.

01:46:53.400 --> 01:46:59.880
[Guest 2]: So, the point is, if the GDP growth is at a 40-year low, and if that does not give you

01:46:59.880 --> 01:47:06.640
[Guest 2]: incentive enough to do the right things, what else will, right?

01:47:06.640 --> 01:47:10.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, 40-year low is like as bad as it could get.

01:47:10.120 --> 01:47:14.240
[Guest 2]: I mean, okay, let's even, I mean, this is nominal, but even when you look at real GDP,

01:47:14.240 --> 01:47:16.320
[Guest 2]: we were at a 10-year low.

01:47:16.320 --> 01:47:21.480
[Guest 2]: So that 10-year low is like, and that 10-year low was also because of the financial crisis,

01:47:21.480 --> 01:47:22.480
[Guest 2]: right?

01:47:22.480 --> 01:47:30.600
[Guest 2]: So, if that does not give our government and our politicians the incentive to do, carry

01:47:30.600 --> 01:47:35.360
[Guest 2]: out the major reforms and do the right things, then, I mean, see, I'm not even, I mean, you

01:47:35.360 --> 01:47:44.680
[Guest 2]: know, people talk about these big philosophical reforms and take something like a goods and

01:47:44.680 --> 01:47:45.680
[Guest 2]: services tax.

01:47:45.680 --> 01:47:51.400
[Guest 2]: Okay, it's been two and a half years since it's been in place.

01:47:51.400 --> 01:47:55.160
[Guest 2]: And every month there is some change, this change, that change, I'm willing to accept

01:47:55.160 --> 01:47:56.160
[Guest 2]: that as well.

01:47:56.160 --> 01:48:02.800
[Guest 2]: But when I upload my return, let that return get uploaded in one time.

01:48:02.800 --> 01:48:06.720
[Guest 2]: Let the OTP come to me, you know, when it has to.

01:48:06.720 --> 01:48:11.720
[Guest 2]: I mean, these things, these are like, you know, the minutest, the simplest of things

01:48:11.720 --> 01:48:18.960
[Guest 2]: that need to be done, or the entire GST system has been made with the assumption that people

01:48:18.960 --> 01:48:24.680
[Guest 2]: will not make mistakes, okay, everyone will file everything and they'll do it correctly.

01:48:24.680 --> 01:48:31.360
[Guest 2]: So recently, I had this experience, one of the media houses I write for raised a query,

01:48:31.360 --> 01:48:37.440
[Guest 2]: and this was regarding a query on an invoice I had generated in 2018-19.

01:48:37.440 --> 01:48:43.600
[Guest 2]: So the date of the invoice did not match with the date I had registered against that invoice

01:48:43.600 --> 01:48:44.600
[Guest 2]: in my return.

01:48:44.600 --> 01:48:48.240
[Guest 2]: Okay, so obviously, they wanted it corrected.

01:48:48.240 --> 01:48:53.320
[Guest 2]: So it seems the law is such that you can only correct a mistake that you make during the

01:48:53.320 --> 01:48:57.040
[Guest 2]: course of that financial year.

01:48:57.040 --> 01:48:58.040
[Guest 2]: This is stupid, right?

01:48:58.040 --> 01:49:00.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, and these are not huge amounts.

01:49:00.640 --> 01:49:05.420
[Guest 2]: I mean, people, you know, it's a 20,000 rupee, 25,000 rupee bill.

01:49:05.420 --> 01:49:10.620
[Guest 2]: So I mean, if people, you know, if you sort of make even changes to these simple things

01:49:10.620 --> 01:49:16.840
[Guest 2]: and make life simpler for people who follow the GST, that in itself will be a huge thing.

01:49:16.840 --> 01:49:18.400
[Guest 2]: But that is also not happening.

01:49:18.400 --> 01:49:19.400
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

01:49:19.400 --> 01:49:24.440
[Amit Varma]: It's been an awesome experience talking to both of you guys addressing high philosophical

01:49:24.440 --> 01:49:30.800
[Amit Varma]: concerns, like the structure of government, as well as, you know, everyday granular problems

01:49:30.800 --> 01:49:33.240
[Amit Varma]: like where is the OTP for my GST filing?

01:49:33.240 --> 01:49:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Ajay, thanks a lot for coming on the show.

01:49:35.240 --> 01:49:36.240
[Amit Varma]: My pleasure.

01:49:36.240 --> 01:49:37.240
[Amit Varma]: Vivek, thanks a lot.

01:49:37.240 --> 01:49:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Thanks.

